# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: british-empire
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:british-empire/1907-imperial-conference] The **1907 Imperial Conference** was convened in London on 15 April 1907 and concluded on 14 May 1907.
[src:british-empire/1907-imperial-conference] During the sessions a resolution was passed renaming this and future meetings Imperial Conferences; previously, they had been called Colonial Conferences.
[src:british-empire/1907-imperial-conference] The chairman of the conference was British prime minister Sir Henry Campbell-Bannerman.
[src:british-empire/1907-imperial-conference] The conference decided to cease referring to self-governing British colonies as colonies and conferred upon them dominion status.
[src:british-empire/1907-imperial-conference] Canada and Australia were referred to as dominions in the conference's statements while Newfoundland Colony and the Colony of New Zealand were granted dominion status by royal proclamation on 26 September.
[src:british-empire/1907-imperial-conference] Natal and Cape Colony would unite with the two Boer colonies of Orange River Colony and Transvaal Colony, which had been given self-government in 1907, to form the Union of South Africa as a dominion in 1910.
[src:british-empire/1907-imperial-conference] The possibilities of Irish Home Rule and self-governance for India were also discussed.
[src:british-empire/1907-imperial-conference] Imperial preference was raised but rejected by the British prime minister due to British support for free trade.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish component of the 1918 United Kingdom general election took place on 14 December 1918.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It was the final United Kingdom general election to be held throughout Ireland, as the next election would happen following Irish independence.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It is a key moment in modern Irish history, seeing the overwhelming defeat of the moderate nationalist Irish Parliamentary Party (IPP), which had dominated the Irish political landscape since the 1880s, and a landslide victory for the radical Sinn Féin party.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin had never previously stood in a general election, but had won six seats in by-elections in 1917–1918.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The party had vowed in its manifesto to establish an independent Irish Republic.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In Ulster, however, the Unionist Party was the most successful party.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the aftermath of the elections, Sinn Féin's elected members refused to attend the British Parliament in Westminster (London), and instead formed a parliament in Dublin, the First Dáil Éireann ("Assembly of Ireland"), which declared Irish independence as a republic.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish War of Independence was conducted under this revolutionary government which sought international recognition, and set about the process of state-building.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The other parties elected in the election were invited by Sinn Féin to join in creating the Dáil Éireann, but declined and took up their seats at Westminster.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In 1918 a system called plural voting was in place in both Britain and Ireland.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Plural voting was a practice whereby one person might be able to vote multiple times in an election.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Property and business owners could vote both in the constituency where their property lay and that in which they lived, if the two were different.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] This system often resulted in one person being able to cast multiple votes.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the newly formed Irish Free State this system was ended by the Electoral Act 1923 and was abolished in the UK by the Representation of the People Act 1948.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Plural voting remained in effect in Northern Ireland until 1969.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The 1918 election was held in the aftermath of World War I, the Easter Rising and the Conscription Crisis.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It was the first general election to be held after the Representation of the People Act 1918.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It was thus the first election in which women over the age of 30, and all men over the age of 21, could vote.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Previously, all women and most working-class men had been excluded from voting.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In 1918 the whole of Ireland was a part of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland, and was represented in the British Parliament by 105 Members of Parliament (MPs).
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Whereas in Great Britain most elected politicians were members of either the Liberal Party or the Conservative Party, from the early 1880s most Irish MPs were Irish nationalists, who sat together in the British House of Commons as the Irish Parliamentary Party.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The IPP strove for Home Rule, that is, limited self-government for Ireland within the United Kingdom, and had been supported by most Irish people, especially the Catholic majority.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Home Rule was opposed by most Protestants in Ireland, who formed a majority of the population in parts of the northern province of Ulster but a minority in the rest of Ireland, and favoured maintenance of the Union with Great Britain (and were therefore called Unionists).
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Unionists were supported by the Conservative Party, whereas from 1885 the Liberal Party was committed to enacting some form of Home Rule.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Unionists eventually formed their own representation, first the Irish Unionist Party then the Ulster Unionist Party.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Home Rule appeared to have been finally achieved with the passing of the Home Rule Act 1914.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, the implementation of the Act was temporarily postponed with the outbreak of World War I due to determined Ulster Unionists' resistance to the Act.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] As the war prolonged and with the failure to make any progress on the issue, the more radical Sinn Féin began to grow in strength.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin was founded by Arthur Griffith in 1905.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He believed that Irish nationalists should emulate the *Ausgleich* of Hungarian nationalists who, in the 19th century under Ferenc Deák, had chosen to boycott the imperial parliament in Vienna and unilaterally established their own legislature in Budapest.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Griffith had favoured a peaceful solution based on 'dual monarchy' with Britain, that is two separate states with a single head of state and a limited central government to control matters of common concern only.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, by 1918, under its new leader Éamon de Valera, Sinn Féin had come to favour achieving separation from Britain by means of an armed uprising if necessary and the establishment of an independent republic.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the aftermath of the 1916 Easter Rising the party's ranks were swelled by participants and supporters of the rebellion as they were freed from British prisons and internment camps, and at its 1917 Ard Fheis (annual conference) de Valera was elected leader and the new, more radical policy adopted.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Prior to 1916, Sinn Féin had been a fringe movement having a limited cooperative alliance with William O'Brien's All-for-Ireland League and enjoyed little electoral success.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, between the Easter Rising of that year and the 1918 general election, the party's popularity increased dramatically.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin demonstrated its new electoral capability in four by-election successes in 1917 in which Count Plunkett, Joseph McGuinness, de Valera and W.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Cosgrave were each elected, although it lost three by-elections in early 1918 before winning two more with Patrick McCartan and Arthur Griffith.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In one case there were unproven allegations of electoral fraud.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The party had benefitted from a number of factors in the 1918 elections, including demographic changes and political factors.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish electorate in 1918, as with the entire electorate throughout the United Kingdom, had changed in two major ways since the preceding general election.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Firstly, there was a "generational" change because of the First World War, which meant that the British general election due in 1915 had not taken place.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] As a result, no election took place between 1910 and 1918, the longest gap in modern British and Irish constitutional history until then (it was superseded in Britain in 1935–45).
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Secondly, the franchise had been greatly extended by the Representation of the People Act 1918.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] This granted voting rights to women (albeit only those over 30) for the first time, and gave all men over 21 and military servicemen over 19 a vote in parliamentary elections without property qualifications.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish electorate increased from around 700,000 to about two million.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Overall, a new generation of young voters, and the sudden influx of women over thirty, meant that vast numbers of new voters of unknown voter affiliation existed, changing dramatically the composition of the Irish electorate.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Six MPs stood under a different political affiliation from the December 1910 general election.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] One MP stood under a different political affiliation from their by-election victory.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Voting in most Irish constituencies occurred on Saturday, 14 December 1918.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] While the rest of the United Kingdom fought the 'Khaki election' on other issues involving the British parties, in Ireland four major political parties had national appeal.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] These were the IPP, Sinn Féin, the Irish Unionist Party and the Irish Labour Party.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Unionist Party favoured continuance of the union with Britain (along with its subordinate, the Ulster Unionist Labour Association, who fought as Labour Unionists).
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] A number of other small nationalist parties also took part.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Ireland had 105 seats elected from 103 constituencies.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Ninety-nine seats were elected from single-seat geographical constituencies under the first-past-the-post voting system.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] There were two two-seat constituencies: Dublin University (Trinity College) elected two MPs under the single transferable vote and Cork City elected two MPs under the bloc voting system.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In addition to ordinary geographical constituencies there were three university constituencies: the Queen's University of Belfast (which returned a Unionist), Dublin University (which returned two Unionists) and the National University (which returned a member of Sinn Féin).
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Of the 105 seats, 25 were uncontested, with a Sinn Féin candidate winning unopposed.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Seventeen of these seats were in Munster.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In some cases it was because there was a certain winner in Sinn Féin.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Dillon was first elected to the Tipperary constituency in 1880.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He resigned in 1883 but was re-elected in 1885.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Donovan contested the Donegal South constituency in 1918.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Esmonde was first elected to the Dublin South constituency in 1885.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Farrell contested the Longford constituency in 1918.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Farrell was first elected to the Cavan West constituency in 1895.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Hazleton contested the Louth constituency in 1918.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Kilbride was first elected to the Kerry South constituency in 1887.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He retired in 1900 but was re-elected in 1903.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Meehan contested the Queen's County constituency in 1918.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Nugent contested the Dublin St Michan's constituency in 1918.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] O'Connor was first elected to the Tipperary constituency in 1885.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He lost his seat in 1892 but regained it in 1905.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] O'Dowd was first elected to the Sligo North constituency in 1900.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] O'Shee contested the Waterford County constituency in 1918.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Lynch contested the Battersea South constituency in 1918.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Lynch was first elected to the Galway Borough constituency in 1901.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He lost his seat in 1903 following his conviction but was re-elected in 1909.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sheehan contested the Stepney Limehouse constituency in 1918.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Gwynn contested the Dublin University constituency in 1918.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sheehan contested the Westmeath constituency in 1918.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In this election, 75 candidates who had never previously been elected to Parliament were elected.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin candidates won 73 seats out of 105, but four party candidates (Arthur Griffith, Éamon de Valera, Eoin MacNeill and Liam Mellows) were elected for two constituencies and so the total number of individual Sinn Féin MPs elected was 69.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Despite the isolated allegations of intimidation and electoral fraud on the part of both republicans and unionists, the election was seen as a landslide victory for Sinn Féin.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin received 46.9% of votes island-wide, and 65% of votes in the area that became the Irish Free State.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, the 46.9% is not the total result of the overall success of Sinn Féin.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] That figure only accounts for 48 seats that they won because in 25 of the other constituencies the other parties did not contest them, and Sinn Féin won them unopposed.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Most of these constituencies were Sinn Féin strongholds.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It has been estimated that, had the 25 seats been contested, Sinn Féin would have received at least 53% of the vote island-wide.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, this is a conservative estimate and the percentage would likely have been higher.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin also did not contest four seats due to a deal with the IPP (see below).
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Labour, who had pulled out in the south under instructions to 'wait', polled better in Belfast than Sinn Féin.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Within the 26 counties that became the Irish Free State, Sinn Féin achieved 400,269 votes in the contested seats out of 606,117 total votes cast which amounted to a huge landslide of 66.0% in the vote and winning 70 out of the 75 constituencies.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish Unionist Party won 22 seats and 25.3% of the vote island-wide (29.2% when Labour Unionist candidates are included), becoming the second-largest party in terms of MPs.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The success of the unionists, who won 26 seats overall, was largely limited to Ulster.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Otherwise, southern unionists were elected only in the constituencies of Rathmines and Dublin University which returned two.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the 26 counties that later became the Irish Free State and then the Republic of Ireland, the Irish Unionist Alliance polled 37,218 votes from 101,839 total votes cast for other parties in the constituencies that they stood a candidate.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, if all of the total votes in the contested seats where the Irish Unionist Alliance did not stand are included there was a total of 606,117 votes cast, which converts the Irish Unionist Alliance share of the vote in the 26 counties to just 6.1%.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] With the one Independent Unionist being elected for Dublin University adding 0.1% in total with 793 votes to give 6.2% across the 26 counties and only 3 seats won by the Unionists.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The IPP suffered a catastrophic defeat including the loss of its leader, John Dillon.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It won only six seats in Ireland, its losses exaggerated by the "first-past-the-post" system which gave it a share of seats far short of its much larger share of the vote (21.7%) and the number of seats it would have won under a "proportional representation" ballot system.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] All but one of its seats were in Ulster.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The exception was Waterford City, the seat previously held by John Redmond, who had died earlier in the year, and retained by his son Captain William Redmond.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Four of their Ulster seats were part of the deal to avoid unionist victories which saved some for the party but may have cost it the support of Protestant voters elsewhere.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The IPP came close to winning other seats in County Louth and Wexford South, and in general their support held up better in the north and east of the island.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The party was represented in Westminster by seven MPs because T.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] O'Connor won the Liverpool Scotland seat he had held since the 1885 election due to Irish emigrant votes.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The remnants of the IPP in time became the Nationalist Party of Northern Ireland under the leadership of Joseph Devlin.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the 26 counties that became the Irish Free State, the Irish Parliamentary Party won 181,320 votes out of 606,117 total votes cast in the contested seats, amounting to a 26.0% vote share.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] If the Independent Home Rule Nationalists are included there were 11,162 votes which comes to 1.8% and a vote share of 27.8% for the Nationalists.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish Parliamentary Party held on to just 2 seats in the 26 counties that became Southern Ireland and then the Irish Free State.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In Ulster (nine counties), Unionists won 23 out of the 38 seats with Sinn Féin gaining ten and the Irish Parliamentary Party five.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] There was a limited electoral pact brokered by Roman Catholic Cardinal Michael Logue in December between Sinn Féin and the Nationalist IPP in eight seats.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, it only concluded after nominations closed.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin instructed its supporters to vote IPP in Armagh South, despite no Unionist candidate (79 SF votes), Down South (33 SF votes for Éamon de Valera), Tyrone North-East (56 SF votes) and Donegal East (46 SF votes).
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The IPP instructed its supporters to vote Sinn Féin in Fermanagh South (132 IPP votes) which had no Unionist candidate, Londonderry City (120 IPP votes) where Eoin MacNeill narrowly beat the Unionist, and Tyrone North-West also against a Unionist but where no IPP candidate was nominated.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The discipline of voters, when faced with two rival nationalist candidates and with only a post-nomination pact, was impressive.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The pact only broke down in Down East where a Unionist won as the IPP candidate refused to participate, thus splitting the Catholic nationalist vote.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] There was no pact in Belfast Falls which Joe Devlin (IPP) won with 8,488 votes against 3,245 for Éamon de Valera (SF) although no Unionist stood.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The only other Belfast seat contested by both nationalist parties was Duncairn against Edward Carson; otherwise, Sinn Féin stood alone in seven seats reaching double figures in two.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Monaghan North was won by Sinn Féin's Ernest Blythe in a three-cornered fight against both IPP and Unionist candidates.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the Monaghan South, and Donegal North, South and West seats, despite no Unionist standing, Sinn Féin won all four against IPP candidates.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin took the two (uncontested) Cavan seats with Arthur Griffith taking his second in Cavan East as well as that of Tyrone North West.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In six contested seats no Unionist stood.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Unionists won a clear majority of the 38 Ulster seats including eight of the nine in Belfast.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the six Ulster counties which formed the future Northern Ireland, Unionists won 23 of the 30 seats.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] On 21 January 1919, 27 (out of 101 elected) members representing thirty constituencies answered the roll of Dáil Éireann—the Irish for "Assembly of Ireland".
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Invitations to attend the Dáil had been sent to all 100 men and one woman who had been elected on 14 December 1918.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Eoin MacNeill had been elected for both Londonderry City and the National University of Ireland.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Thirty-three republicans were unable to attend as they were in prison, most of them without trial since 17 May 1918.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Pierce McCan (of Tipperary East), who died in prison, would have brought the total to thirty-four.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Of the 69 republicans elected, most had fought in the Easter Rising.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In accordance with the Sinn Féin manifesto, their elected members refused to attend Westminster, having instead formed their own parliament.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Dáil Éireann was, according to John Patrick McCarthy, the revolutionary government under which the Irish War of Independence was fought and which sought international recognition.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Maryann Gialanella Valiulis says that having justified its existence, the Dáil provided itself with a theoretical framework and set about the process of state-building.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] After having dominated Irish politics for four decades, the IPP was so decimated by its massive defeat that it dissolved soon after the election.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] As mentioned above, its remains became the Northern Ireland-based Nationalist Party, which survived in Northern Ireland until 1969.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The British administration and unionists refused to recognise the Dáil.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] At its first meeting attended by 27 deputies (others were still imprisoned or impaired) on 21 January 1919 the Dáil issued a Declaration of Independence and proclaimed itself the parliament of a new state, the Irish Republic.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] On the same day, in unconnected circumstances, two members of the Royal Irish Constabulary guarding gelignite were killed in the Soloheadbeg Ambush by members of the Irish Volunteers.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Although it had not ordered this incident, the course of events soon drove the Dáil to recognise the Volunteers as the army of the Irish Republic and the ambush as an act of war against Great Britain.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Volunteers therefore changed their name, in August, to the Irish Republican Army.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The train of events set in motion by the elections would eventually bring about the creation of the Irish Free State as a British dominion in 1922.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] That state became the first internationally recognised independent Irish state in 1931, when the Statute of Westminster removed virtually all of the UK Parliament's remaining authority over the Free State and the other dominions.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Free State eventually evolved into the modern Republic of Ireland.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The leaders of the Sinn Féin candidates elected in 1918, such as de Valera, Michael Collins and W.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Cosgrave, came to dominate Irish politics.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] De Valera, for example, would hold some form of elected office from his first election as an MP in a by-election in 1917 until 1973.
[src:british-empire/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The two major parties in the Republic of Ireland today, Fianna Fáil and Fine Gael, are both descendants of Sinn Féin, which first enjoyed substantial electoral success in 1918.
[src:british-empire/1923-imperial-conference] The **1923 Imperial Conference** met in London in the autumn of 1923, the first attended by the new Irish Free State.
[src:british-empire/1923-imperial-conference] While named the **Imperial Economic Conference**, the principal activity concerned the rights of the Dominions in regards to determining their own foreign policy.
[src:british-empire/1923-imperial-conference] The conference occurred in the wake of several important developments in Empire diplomacy.
[src:british-empire/1923-imperial-conference] The Chanak Crisis of 1922 was a threatened military conflict between the newly formed Republic of Turkey and the United Kingdom.
[src:british-empire/1923-imperial-conference] During the crisis, the British cabinet issued a communiqué threatening to declare war against Turkey on behalf of the UK and the Dominions.
[src:british-empire/1923-imperial-conference] The other Dominion prime ministers failed to support Lloyd George's action.
[src:british-empire/1923-imperial-conference] When a new peace treaty, the Treaty of Lausanne, was negotiated with Turkey in 1923, the Dominion governments did not participate in the negotiations or sign and they declared that the UK acted only for itself and not on behalf of the Dominions.
[src:british-empire/1923-imperial-conference] In addition, prior to the Imperial Conference, Canada negotiated the Halibut Treaty with the United States and did so without involving the United Kingdom or allowing the British government to sign on Canada's behalf.
[src:british-empire/1923-imperial-conference] This was a departure from earlier practice in which the British government had sole responsibility for imperial foreign affairs and a constitutional right to conduct foreign policy on behalf of the dominions, including signing treaties on their behalf.
[src:british-empire/1923-imperial-conference] The British, Australian, and New Zealand governments wished the conference to adopt a broad common foreign policy statement however Canadian Prime Minister William Lyon Mackenzie King and South African Prime Minister J.
[src:british-empire/1923-imperial-conference] Hertzog argued that allowing the conference to make decisions that were binding on the dominions would encroach on their autonomy and that foreign policy of each Dominion should be determined by that Dominion's parliament (henceforth referred to as the King-Hertzog principle).
[src:british-empire/1923-imperial-conference] The Conference affirmed the Canadian position that dominions had the right to pursue their own foreign policy autonomously from Britain and the Empire and could negotiate and sign treaties on their own behalf.
[src:british-empire/1923-imperial-conference] It was also recognised that each member of the Empire was obliged to avoid taking any action that would injure another member and that neither the Dominion governments nor the British government could commit another to an action without its consent.
[src:british-empire/1923-imperial-conference] Commenting on this speech African-American historian and Pan-Africanist W.
[src:british-empire/1923-imperial-conference] Du Bois wrote that "This almost naïve setting of the darker races beyond the pale of democracy and of modern humanity was listened to with sympathetic attention in England.
[src:british-empire/1923-imperial-conference] On the issue of trade, Australian prime minister Stanley Bruce lobbied hard and consistently for the Conservative government of Stanley Baldwin to make changes to Great Britain's trading arrangements to give preference to Dominion products over imports from elsewhere.
[src:british-empire/1923-imperial-conference] Bruce argued for Empire-wide economic trading arrangements that would see domestic demands filled by production from member states before seeking supplemental imports from other countries and empires.
[src:british-empire/1923-imperial-conference] Baldwin and the Conservatives would attempt to introduce such a scheme in Britain; however, the British public feared higher prices for basic products (particularly food), and this fear was a factor in the Conservative government's defeat in the election of December 1923.
[src:british-empire/1923-imperial-conference] Baldwin's successor Ramsay MacDonald repudiated the plan and it would not see fruition until the British Empire Economic Conference of 1932.
[src:british-empire/1926-imperial-conference] The **1926 Imperial Conference** was the fifth Imperial Conference bringing together the prime ministers of the Dominions of the British Empire.
[src:british-empire/1926-imperial-conference] It was held in London from 19 October to 23 November 1926.
[src:british-empire/1926-imperial-conference] The conference was notable for producing the Balfour Declaration, which established the principle that the dominions are all equal in status, and "autonomous communities within the British Empire" not subordinate to the United Kingdom.
[src:british-empire/1926-imperial-conference] The term "Commonwealth" was officially adopted to describe the community.
[src:british-empire/1926-imperial-conference] The conference was arranged to follow directly after the 1926 Assembly of the League of Nations (in Geneva, Switzerland), to reduce the amount of travelling required for the dominions' representatives.
[src:british-empire/1926-imperial-conference] The conference created the Inter-Imperial Relations Committee, chaired by Arthur Balfour, to look into future constitutional arrangements for the Commonwealth.
[src:british-empire/1926-imperial-conference] In the end, the committee rejected the idea of a codified constitution, as espoused by South Africa's former Prime Minister Jan Smuts, but also fell short of endorsing the "end of empire" espoused by Smuts's arch-rival, Barry Hertzog.
[src:british-empire/1926-imperial-conference] The recommendations were adopted unanimously by the conference on 15 November, followed by an equally warm reception in the newspapers.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] A popular uprising by Palestinian Arabs in Mandatory Palestine against the British administration, known as the **Great Revolt**, and later the **Great Palestinian Revolt** or the **Palestinian Revolution**, lasted from 1936 until 1939.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The movement sought independence from British colonial rule and the end of British support for Zionism, including Jewish immigration and land sales to Jews.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The uprising occurred during a peak in the influx of European Jewish immigrants, and with the growing plight of the rural fellahin rendered landless, who as they moved to metropolitan centres to escape their abject poverty found themselves socially marginalized.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] A month into the disturbances, Amin al-Husseini, president of the Arab Higher Committee and Mufti of Jerusalem, declared 16 May 1936 as "Palestine Day" and called for a general strike.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] David Ben-Gurion, leader of the Yishuv, described Arab causes as fear of growing Jewish economic power, opposition to mass Jewish immigration and fear of the British identification with Zionism.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The general strike lasted from April to October 1936.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The revolt is often analysed in terms of two distinct phases.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The first phase began as spontaneous popular resistance, which was seized on by the urban bourgeois Arab Higher Committee, giving the movement an organized shape that was focused mainly on strikes and other forms of political protest, in order to secure a political result.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] By October 1936, this phase had been defeated by the British civil administration using a combination of political concessions, international diplomacy (involving the rulers of Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Transjordan and Yemen) and the threat of martial law.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The second phase, which began late in 1937, was a peasant-led resistance movement provoked by British repression in 1936 in which increasingly British forces were targeted as the army itself increasingly targeted the villages it thought supportive of the revolt.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] During this phase, the rebellion was brutally suppressed by the British Army and the Palestine Police Force using repressive measures that were intended to intimidate the whole population and undermine popular support for the revolt.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] According to official British figures covering the whole revolt, the army and police killed more than 2,000 Arabs in combat, 108 were hanged, and 961 died because of what they described as "gang and terrorist activities".
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In an analysis of the British statistics, Walid Khalidi estimates 19,792 casualties for the Arabs, with 5,032 dead: 3,832 killed by the British and 1,200 dead due to intracommunal terrorism, and 14,760 wounded.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] By one estimate, ten percent of the adult male Palestinian Arab population between 20 and 60 was killed, wounded, imprisoned or exiled.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Estimates of the number of Palestinian Jews killed are up to several hundred.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Arab revolt in Mandatory Palestine was unsuccessful, and its consequences affected the outcome of the 1948 Palestine war.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] It caused the British Mandate to give crucial support to pre-state Zionist militias like the Haganah, whereas on the Palestinian Arab side, the revolt forced the main Palestinian Arab leader of the period, al-Husseini, into exile.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] World War I left Palestine, especially the countryside, deeply impoverished.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Ottoman and then the Mandate authorities levied high taxes on farming and agricultural produce and during the 1920s and 1930s this together with a fall in prices, cheap imports, natural disasters and paltry harvests all contributed to the increasing indebtedness of the fellahin.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] By 1931 the 106,400 dunums of low-lying Category A farming land in Arab possession supported a farming population of 590,000 whereas the 102,000 dunums of such land in Jewish possession supported a farming population of only 50,000.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The late 1920s witnessed poor harvests, and the consequent immiseration grew even harsher with the onset of the Great Depression and the collapse of commodity prices.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Economic factors played a major role in the outbreak of the Arab revolt.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Palestine's fellahin, the country's peasant farmers, made up over two-thirds of the indigenous Arab population and from the 1920s onwards they were pushed off the land in increasingly large numbers into urban environments where they often encountered only poverty and social marginalisation.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Many were crowded into shanty towns in Jaffa and Haifa where some found succour and encouragement in the teachings of the charismatic preacher Izz ad-Din al-Qassam who worked among the poor in Haifa.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The revolt was thus a popular uprising that produced its own leaders and developed into a national revolt.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Although the Mandatory government introduced measures to limit the transfer of land from Arabs to Jews, these were easily circumvented by willing buyers and sellers.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The failure of the authorities to invest in economic growth and healthcare for the general Palestinian public and the Zionist policy of ensuring that their investments were directed only to facilitate expansion exclusively of the Yishuv further compounded matters.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] After 1935 the slump in the construction boom and further concentration by the Yishuv on an exclusivist Hebrew labour programme removed most of the sources of employment for rural migrants.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] By 1935 only 12,000 Arabs (5% of the workforce) worked in the Jewish sector, half of these in agriculture, whereas 32,000 worked for the Mandate authorities and 211,000 were either self-employed or worked for Arab employers.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] At the same time, Jewish immigration peaked in 1935, just months before Palestinian Arabs began their full-scale, nationwide revolt.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In 1936 alone, some 60,000 Jews immigrated that year – the Jewish population having grown under British auspices from 57,000 to 320,000 in 1935.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The advent of Zionism and British colonial administration crystallised Palestinian nationalism and the desire to defend indigenous traditions and institutions.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Palestinian society was largely clan-based (*hamula*), with an urban land-holding elite lacking a centralised leadership.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The expansion of education, the development of civil society and of transportation, communications, and especially of broadcasting and other media, all facilitated notable changes.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Yishuv itself, at the same time, was steadily building the structures for its own state-building with public organisations like the Jewish Agency and the covert creation and consolidation of a paramilitary arm with the Haganah and Irgun.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In 1930 Sheikh Izz ad-Din al-Qassam organised and established the Black Hand, a small anti-Zionist and anti-British militia.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] He recruited and arranged military training for impoverished but pious peasants but also for ex-criminals he had persuaded to take Islam seriously and they engaged in a campaign of vandalizing tree plantations and British-constructed rail lines, destroying phone lines and disrupting transportation.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The pressures of the 1930s wrought several changes, giving rise to new political organizations and a broader activism that spurred a far wider cross-section of the population in rural areas, strongly nationalist, to join actively in the Palestinian cause.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Youth organisations emerged like Young Men's Muslim Association and the Youth Congress Party, the former anti-Zionist, the latter pan-Arab.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Palestinian Boy Scout Movement, founded early in 1936, became active in the general strike.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Myriads of rural women would play an important role in response to *faz'a* alarm calls for inter-village help by rallying in defence of the rebellion.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] General strikes had been used in neighbouring Arab countries to place political pressures on Western colonial powers.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In Iraq a general strike in July 1931, accompanied by organised demonstrations in the streets, led to independence for the former British mandate territory under Prime Minister Nuri as-Said, and full membership of the League of Nations in October 1932.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Syrian National Bloc had used a general strike from 20 January to 6 March in 1936 which, despite harsh reprisals, brought about negotiations in Paris that led to a Franco-Syrian Treaty of Independence.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] This showed that determined economic and political pressure could challenge a fragile imperial administration.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] On 16 October 1935 a large arms shipment camouflaged in cement bins, comprising 25 Lewis guns and their bipods, 800 rifles and 400,000 rounds of ammunition destined for the Haganah, was discovered during unloading at the port of Jaffa.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The news sparked Arab fears of a Jewish military takeover of Palestine.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] A little over two weeks later, on 2 November 1935, al-Qassam gave a speech in the port of Haifa denouncing the Balfour declaration on its 18th anniversary.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In a proclamation to that effect, together with Jamal al-Husayni, he alluded to the Haganah weapons smuggling operation.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Questioned at the time by a confidant about his preparations, he stated that he had 15 men, each furnished with a rifle and one cartridge.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Soon after, perhaps fearing a pending preemptive arrest, he disappeared with his group into the hills, not to start a revolution, premature at that point, but to impress upon people that he was a man ready to do what he said should be done.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Some weeks later, a Jewish policeman was shot dead in a citrus grove while investigating the theft of grapefruit, after he happened to come close to the Qassamites' encampment.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Following the incident, the Palestine police launched a massive manhunt and surrounded al-Qassam in a cave just north of Ya'bad.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In the ensuing battle, on 20 November, al-Qassam was killed.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The death of al-Qassam generated widespread outrage among Palestinian Arabs, galvanizing public sentiments with an impact similar to the effect on the Yishuv of news of the death of Joseph Trumpeldor in 1920 at the Tel Hai settlement.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Huge crowds gathered for the occasion of his obsequies in Haifa and later burial in Balad al-Shaykh.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] One of the three, Israel Chazan, was from Thessaloniki.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Salonican community's request that permission be granted to allow them to conduct a solemn funeral for Chasan was turned down by the district commissioner, who had allowed al-Qassam a ceremonial burial some months earlier.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The refusal sparked a demonstration by 30,000 Jews in Tel Aviv who overcame the police and maltreated Arab labourers and damaged property in Jaffa.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The following day, two Arab workers sleeping in a hut in a banana plantation beside the highway between Petah Tikva and Yarkona were assassinated in retaliation by members of the Haganah-Bet.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Jews and Palestinians attacked each other in and around Tel Aviv.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Palestinians in Jaffa rampaged through a Jewish residential area, resulting in several Jewish deaths.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] After four days, by 19 April, the deteriorating situation erupted into a set of countrywide disturbances.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] An Arab general strike and revolt ensued that lasted until October 1936.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The strike began on 19 April in Nablus, where an Arab National Committee was formed, and by the end of the month National Committees had been formed in all of the towns and some of the larger villages.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] On the same day, the High Commissioner Wauchope issued Emergency Regulations that laid the legal basis for suppressing the insurgency.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] On 21 April the leaders of the five main parties accepted the decision at Nablus and called for a general strike of all Arabs engaged in labour, transport and shopkeeping for the following day.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] While the strike was initially organised by workers and local committees, under pressure from below, political leaders became involved to help with co-ordination.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] This led to the formation on 25 April 1936 of the Arab Higher Committee (AHC).
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] About one month after the general strike started, the leadership group declared a general non-payment of taxes in explicit opposition to Jewish immigration.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In the countryside, armed insurrection started sporadically, becoming more organized over time.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] One particular target of the rebels was the Mosul–Haifa oil pipeline of the Iraq Petroleum Company constructed only a few years earlier to Haifa from a point on the Jordan River south of Lake Tiberias.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] This was repeatedly bombed at various points along its length.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Other attacks were on railways (including trains) and on civilian targets such as Jewish settlements, secluded Jewish neighbourhoods in the mixed cities, and Jews, both individually and in groups.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] During the summer of that year, thousands of Jewish-farmed acres and orchards were destroyed, Jewish civilians were attacked and murdered, and some Jewish communities, such as those in Beisan and Acre, fled to safer areas.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The measures taken against the strike were harsh from the outset and grew harsher as the revolt deepened.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Unable to contain the protests with the two battalions already stationed in the country, Britain inundated Palestine with soldiers from regiments all over the empire, including its Egyptian garrison.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The drastic measures taken included house searches without warrants, night raids, preventive detention, caning, flogging, deportation, confiscation of property, and torture.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] As early as May 1936 the British formed armed Jewish units equipped with armoured vehicles to serve as auxiliary police.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In reality the measures created a sense of solidarity between the villagers and the rebels.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] On 2 June, an attempt by rebels to derail a train bringing the 2nd Battalion Bedfordshire and Hertfordshire Regiment from Egypt led to the railways being put under guard, placing a great strain on the security forces.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] On 4 June, in response to this situation, the government rounded up a large number of Palestinian leaders and sent them to a detention camp at Auja al-Hafir in the Negev desert.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Battle of Nur Shams on 21 June marked an escalation with the largest engagement of British troops against Arab militants so far in this Revolt.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] During July, Arab volunteers from Syria and Transjordan, led by Fawzi al-Qawukji, helped the rebels to divide their formations into four fronts, each led by a District Commander who had armed platoons of 150–200 fighters, each commanded by a platoon leader.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] A Statement of Policy issued by the Colonial Office in London on 7 September declared the situation a "direct challenge to the authority of the British Government in Palestine" and announced the appointment of Lieutenant-General John Dill as supreme military commander.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] By the end of September 20,000 British troops in Palestine were deployed to "round up Arab bands".
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In June 1936 the British involved their clients in Transjordan, Iraq, Saudi Arabia and Egypt in an attempt to pacify the Palestinian Arabs and on 9 October the rulers made an appeal for the strike to be ended.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] A more pressing concern may have been the approaching citrus harvest and the attractive, soaring prices on the international markets caused by the disruption to the Spanish citrus harvest due to the Spanish Civil War.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] On 22 August 1936, Anglo-Jewish Arabist scholar Levi Billig of Hebrew University was murdered in his home outside Jerusalem by an Arab assassin, one of three Jews killed by Arabs on 22 August, and one of 73 Jews killed since the beginning of the Arab armed insurrection.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The strike was called off on 11 October 1936 and the violence abated for about a year while the Peel Commission deliberated.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Royal Commission was announced on 18 May 1936 and its members were appointed on 29 July, but the Commission did not arrive in Palestine until 11 November.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In the early 1920s the first High Commissioner of Palestine, Herbert Samuel, had failed to create a unified political structure embracing both Palestinian Arabs and Palestinian Jews in constitutional government with joint political institutions.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] This failure facilitated internal institutional partition in which the Jewish Agency exercised a degree of autonomous control over the Jewish settlement and the Supreme Muslim Council performed a comparable role for Muslims.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Thus, well before Lord Peel arrived in Palestine on 11 November 1936, the groundwork for territorial partition as proposed by the Royal Commission in its report on 7 July 1937 had already been done.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Peel's main recommendation was for partition of Palestine into a small Jewish state (based on current Jewish land ownership population and incorporating the country's most productive agricultural land), a residual Mandatory area, and a larger Arab state linked to Transjordan.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] A second and more radical proposal was for transfer of 225,000 Palestinian Arabs from the proposed Jewish state to a future Arab state and Transjordan.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] It is likely that Zionist leaders played a role in persuading Peel to accept the notion of transfer, which had been a strand of Zionist ideology from its inception.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Arab Higher Committee rejected the recommendations immediately, as did the Jewish Revisionists.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Initially, the religious Zionists, some of the General Zionists, and sections of the Labour Zionist movement also opposed the recommendations.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The British government initially accepted the Peel report in principle.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] However, with war clouds looming over Europe, they realized that to attempt to implement it against the will of the Palestinian Arab majority would rouse up the entire Arab world against Britain.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The Woodhead Commission considered three different plans, one of which was based on the Peel plan.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Reporting in 1938, the Commission rejected the Peel plan primarily on the grounds that it could not be implemented without a massive forced transfer of Arabs (an option that the British government had already ruled out).
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] With dissent from some of its members, the Commission instead recommended a plan that would leave the Galilee under British mandate, but emphasised serious problems with it that included a lack of financial self-sufficiency of the proposed Arab State.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The British Government accompanied the publication of the Woodhead Report by a statement of policy rejecting partition as impracticable due to "political, administrative and financial difficulties".
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] With the failure of the Peel Commission's proposals the revolt resumed during the autumn of 1937 marked by the assassination on 26 September of Acting District Commissioner of the Galilee Lewis Andrews by Quassemite gunmen in Nazareth.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Andrews was widely hated by Palestinians for supporting Jewish settlement in the Galilee, and he openly advised Jews to create their own defense force.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] On 30 September, regulations were issued allowing the Government to detain political deportees in any part of the British Empire, and authorising the High Commissioner to outlaw associations whose objectives he regarded as contrary to public policy.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In November 1937, the Irgun formally rejected the policy of Havlagah and embarked on a series of indiscriminate attacks against Arab civilians as a form of what the group called "active defense" against Arab attacks on Jewish civilians.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The British authorities set up military courts, which were established for the trial of offenses connected with the carrying and discharge of firearms, sabotage and intimidation.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Despite this, however, the Arab campaign of murder and sabotage continued and Arab gangs in the hills took on the appearance of organised guerrilla fighters.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In July 1938, when the Palestine Government seemed to have largely lost control of the situation, the garrison was strengthened from Egypt, and in September it was further reinforced from England.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] The police were placed under the operational control of the army commander, and military officials superseded the civil authorities in the enforcement of order.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] In October the Old City of Jerusalem, which had become a rebel stronghold, was reoccupied by the troops.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] By the end of the year a semblance of order had been restored in the towns, but terrorism continued in rural areas until the outbreak of the Second World War.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] Despite cooperation of the Yishuv with the British to quell the revolt, some incidents towards the end of the conflict indicated a coming change in relations.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] On 12 June 1939, A British explosives expert was killed trying to defuse an Irgun bomb near a Jerusalem post office.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p01] On 26 August, two British police officers, Inspector Ronald Barker and Inspector Ralph Cairns, commander of the Jewish Department of the C.I.D., were killed by an Irgun mine in Jerusalem.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Military law allowed swift prison sentences to be passed.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Thousands of Arabs were held in administrative detention, without trial, and without proper sanitation, in overcrowded prison camps.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The British had already formalised the principle of collective punishment in Palestine in the 1924–1925 Collective Responsibility and Punishment Ordinances and updated these ordinances in 1936 with the Collective Fines Ordinance.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Following the Arab capture of the Old City of Jerusalem in October 1938, the army effectively took over Jerusalem and then all of Palestine.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The main form of collective punishment employed by the British forces was destruction of property.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Sometimes entire villages were reduced to rubble, as happened to Mi'ar in October 1938; more often several prominent houses were blown up and others were trashed inside.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The biggest single act of destruction occurred in Jaffa on 16 June 1936, when large gelignite charges were used to cut long pathways through the old city, destroying 220–240 buildings and rendering up to 6,000 Arabs homeless.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Scathing criticism for this action from Palestine Chief Justice Sir Michael McDonnell was not well received by the administration and the judge was soon removed from the country.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Villages were also frequently punished by fines and confiscation of livestock.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The British even used sea mines from the battleship HMS *Malaya* to destroy houses.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In addition to actions against property, a large amount of brutality by the British forces occurred, including beatings, torture and extrajudicial killings.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] A surprisingly large number of prisoners were "shot while trying to escape".
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Several incidents involved serious atrocities, such as massacres at al-Bassa and Halhul.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] As well as destroying the village the RUR and men from the Royal Engineers collected around fifty men from al-Bassa and blew some of them up with explosion under a bus.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The other villagers were then forced to bury the bodies in a pit.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The report was issued in response to growing concern at the severity of the military measures amongst the general public in Great Britain, among members of the British Government, and among governments in countries neighbouring Palestine.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In addition to actions against villages the British Army also conducted punitive actions in the cities.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In Nablus in August 1938 almost 5,000 men were held in a cage for two days and interrogated one after another.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] During their detention the city was searched and then each of the detainees was marked with a rubber stamp on his release.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] At one point a night curfew was imposed on most of the cities.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] It was common British army practice to use local Arabs as human shields by forcing them to ride with military convoys to prevent mine attacks and sniping incidents: soldiers would tie the hostages to the bonnets of lorries, or put them on small flatbeds on the front of trains.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The army told the hostages that any of them who tried to run away would be shot.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] British troops also left Arab wounded on the battlefield to die and maltreated Arab fighters taken in battle, so much so that the rebels tried to remove their wounded or dead from the field of battle.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Sometimes, soldiers would occupy villages, expel all of the inhabitants and remain for months.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Army even burned the bodies of "terrorists" to prevent their funerals becoming the focus of protests.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Sir Charles Tegart was a senior police officer brought into Palestine from the colonial force of British India on 21 October 1937.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Tegart and his deputy David Petrie (later head of MI5) advised a greater emphasis on foreign intelligence gathering and closure of Palestine's borders.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Like many of those enrolled in the Palestinian gendarmerie, Tegart had served in Great Britain's repression of the Irish War of Independence, and the security proposals he introduced exceeded measures adopted down to this time elsewhere in the British Empire.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] 70 fortresses were erected throughout the country at strategic choke points and near Palestinian villages which, if assessed as "bad", were subjected to collective punishment.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Tegart recommended the construction of a frontier road with a barbed wire fence, which became known as Tegart's wall, along the borders with Lebanon and Syria to help prevent the flow of insurgents, goods and weapons.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Tegart encouraged close co-operation with the Jewish Agency.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] It was built by the Histadrut construction company Solel Boneh.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Army forced the fellahin to work on the roads without pay.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Tegart introduced Arab Investigation Centres where prisoners were subjected to beatings, foot whipping (bastinado), electric shocks, denailing and what is now known as "waterboarding".
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Tegart also imported Doberman Pinschers from South Africa and set up a special centre in Jerusalem to train interrogators in torture.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Royal Air Force developed close air support into its then most refined form during the Arab Revolt.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Air patrols had been found effective in keeping convoys and trains free from attack, but this did not help to expose insurgents to battle conditions likely to cause their defeat.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] From the middle of June 1936 wireless vehicles accompanied all convoys and patrols.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] During rebel attacks these vehicles could issue emergency "XX calls" (XX with a coded location), which were given priority over all other radio traffic, to summon aerial reinforcements.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Bombers, which were usually airborne within five minutes, could then either attack insurgents directly or "fix" their position for infantry troops.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Forty-seven such XX calls were issued during the revolt, causing heavy losses to the rebels.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In the June 1936 Battle of Nur Shams British planes attacked Arab irregulars with machine gun fire.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] This use of air power was so successful that the British were able to reduce the regular garrison.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In 1936 an Air Staff Officer in Middle East Command based in the Kingdom of Egypt, Arthur Harris, known as an advocate of "air policing", commented on the revolt saying that "one 250 lb. or 500 lb. bomb in each village that speaks out of turn" would satisfactorily solve the problem.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In 1937 Harris was promoted to Air Commodore and in 1938 he was posted to Palestine and Trans-Jordan as Air Officer Commanding the RAF contingent in the region until September 1939.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] "Limited" bombing attacks on Arab villages were carried out by the RAF, although at times this involved razing whole villages.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Harris described the system by which recalcitrant villages were kept under control by aerial bombardment as "Air-Pin".
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Aircraft of the RAF were also used to drop propaganda leaflets over Palestinian towns and villages telling the fellahin that they were the main sufferers of the rebellion and threatening an increase in taxes.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Low flying RAF squadrons were able to produce detailed intelligence on the location of road blocks, sabotaged bridges, railways and pipelines.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] RAF aerial photographs were also used to build up a detailed map of Arab population distribution.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Although the British Army was responsible for setting up the Arab counter-insurgent forces (known as the peace bands) and supplying them with arms and money these were operated by RAF Intelligence, commanded by Patrick Domville.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] At the beginning of the revolt RAF assets in the region comprised a bomber flight at RAF Ramleh, an RAF armoured car flight at Ramleh, fourteen bomber squadrons at RAF Amman, and a RAF armoured car company at Ma'an.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] At the beginning of the Revolt crew from the Haifa Naval Force's two cruisers were used to carry out tasks ashore, manning two howitzers and naval lorries equipped with QF 2 pounder naval guns and searchlights used to disperse Arab snipers.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] From the end of June two destroyers were used to patrol the coast of Palestine in a bid to prevent gun running.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] These searched as many as 150 vessels per week and were an effective preventive measure.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] At the request of the Army additional naval platoons landed in July to help protect Haifa and Jewish settlements in the surrounding countryside.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Navy also relieved the Army of duties in Haifa by using nine naval platoons to form the *Haifa Town Force* and in August three naval platoons were landed to support the police.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Following publication of the Peel Commission's report in July 1937 HMS *Repulse* sailed to Haifa where landing parties were put ashore to maintain calm.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Various other naval vessels continued with this role until the end of the revolt.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Following the Irgun's detonation of a large bomb in a market in Haifa on 6 July 1938 the High Commissioner signalled the Commander-in-Chief of the Mediterranean Fleet, Admiral Sir Dudley Pound, requesting the assistance of naval vessels capable of providing landing parties.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Pound dispatched HMS *Repulse* and diverted HMS *Emerald* to Haifa, which arrived the same day and landed five platoons, one to each police district.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] HMS *Repulse* relieved HMS *Emerald* the following day and after another bomb was detonated on 10 July five platoons from the ship, made up of sailors and Royal Marines, dispersed mobs and patrolled the city.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] On 11 July provision of three platoons from *Repulse* released men of the West Kent Regiment for a punitive mission against Arabs who had attacked a Jewish colony near Haifa.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] By 17 July the *Repulse* established a Company Headquarters where seamen and Royal Marines manned a 3.7-inch howitzer.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Sailors, Royal Marines, and men of the Suffolk Regiment, who had embarked on the *Repulse*, accompanied foot patrols of the Palestine Police Force.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The *Repulse*, HMS *Hood* and HMS *Warspite* provided howitzer crews which were sent ashore to combat gun running near the border with Lebanon.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Detained Arabs were used to build emplacements and the howitzers were moved quickly between these positions by day and night to confuse bandits as to the likely direction of fire.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Periodically, the guns were used to fire warning rounds close to the vicinity of villages believed to have rebel sympathies.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Britain had completed the modern deep-sea port in Haifa in 1933 and finished laying a pipeline from the Iraqi oilfields to Haifa in 1935, shortly before the outbreak of the revolt.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] A refinery for processing oil from the pipeline was completed by Consolidated Refineries Ltd, a company jointly owned by British Petroleum and Royal Dutch Shell, in December 1939.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] These facilities enhanced the strategic importance of Palestine and of Haifa in particular in Britain's control of the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Arab Revolt was the last major test of Britain's security services in the Middle East before World War II.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The rebellion had brought together urban nationalism and peasant economic grievances arising from rural poverty and landlessness, which was blamed on British misrule.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Accordingly, the Palestinian revolt targeted the political and economic apparatus of the British colonial state, including the communications network, pipelines, police stations, army outposts and British personnel.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] It was this aspect of the revolt, rather than attacks on Jews or violence between rivals for leadership of the national movement, that most concerned the high commissioner.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The mandate authorities were further disturbed by the unity of purpose displayed during the six-month general strike and by the resurgence of pan-Arab nationalism as evidenced by the rise of the Istiqlal Party.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In response to these challenges the British army command ("I" Branch) and battalion headquarters across Palestine issued a daily intelligence bulletin every afternoon detailing political developments.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Special Service Officers (SSOs) assigned to intelligence gathering reported directly to their local command headquarters and their cars were equipped with wireless transmitters so that high grade intelligence could be reported directly to "I" Branch immediately.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] These sources of intelligence gradually became more important than those of the C.I.D. in Palestine, which had been dependent on Arab informers, and which were no longer reliable.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In September 1937, the Jewish Agency appointed Reuven Zaslany liaison officer for intelligence and security affairs between the Political Department of the Jewish Agency and the intelligence arms of the Royal Air Force and the C.I.D.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Zaslany sifted through intelligence collected by Jewish-controlled field operatives and forwarded it to the British military.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He was a frequent visitor at the headquarters of British intelligence and the army, the police and C.I.D. and he also travelled to Damascus to liaise with the Arab opposition's peace bands and with the British Consul in Iraq.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Colonel Frederick Kisch, a British army officer and Zionist leader, was appointed chief liaison officer between the British army and the Jewish Agency Executive with Zaslany as his deputy.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In 1937 the Jewish Agency's intelligence groups were responsible for bugging the Peel Commission hearings in Palestine.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The *Haganah* (Hebrew for "defence"), a Jewish paramilitary organisation, actively supported British efforts to suppress the uprising, which reached 10,000 Arab fighters at their peak during the summer and fall of 1938.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Although the British administration did not officially recognise the *Haganah*, the British security forces cooperated with it by forming the Jewish Settlement Police, Jewish Supernumerary Police, and Special Night Squads.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Special Night Squads engaged in activities described by colonial administrator Sir Hugh Foot, as 'extreme and cruel' involving torture, whipping, abuse and execution of Arabs.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Independently of the British, *Ta'as*, the Haganah's clandestine munitions industry, developed an 81-mm mortar and manufactured mines and grenades, 17,500 of the latter being produced for use during the revolt.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The administration also provided security services to Jewish commercial concerns at cost.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Jewish and British officials worked together to co-ordinate manhunts and collective actions against villages and also discussed the imposition of penalties and sentences.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The rebellion also inspired the Jewish Agency to expand the intelligence-gathering of its Political Department and especially of its Arab Division, with the focus changing from political to military intelligence.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Arab Division set up a network of Jewish controllers and Arab agents around the country.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Some of the intelligence gathered was shared with the British administration, the exchange of information sometimes being conducted by Moshe Shertok, then head of the Jewish Agency, directly with the high commissioner himself.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Shertok also advised the administration on political affairs, on one occasion convincing the high commissioner not to arrest Professor Joseph Klausner, a Revisionist Maximalist activist who had played a key role in the riots of 1929, because of the likely negative consequences.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] There was no single body within the Jewish settlement capable of co-ordinating intelligence gathering before 1939.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Until then there were four separate organisations without any regular or formal liaison.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In mid-1939 the effort to co-ordinate the activities of these groups was led by Shaul Avigur and Moshe Shertok.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In 1931, a Revisionist underground splinter group broke off from Haganah, calling itself the *Irgun* organisation (or *Etzel*).
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The organisation took its orders from Revisionist leader Ze'ev Jabotinsky who was at odds with the dominant Labour Zionist movement led by David Ben-Gurion.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The rift between the two Zionist movements further deteriorated in 1933 when two Revisionists were blamed for the murder of Haim Arlosoroff, who had negotiated the Haavara Agreement between the Jewish Agency and Nazi Germany.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Ultimately, however, the events of the Arab Revolt blurred the differences between the gradualist approach of Ben-Gurion and the Maximalist Iron Wall approach of Jabotinsky and turned militarist patriotism into a bipartisan philosophy.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Indeed, Ben-Gurion's own Special Operations Squads conducted a punitive operation in the Arab village of Lubya firing weapons into a room through a window killing two men and one woman and injuring three people, including two children.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] From October 1937 the Irgun instituted a wave of bombings against Arab crowds and buses.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] For the first time in the conflict massive bombs were placed in crowded Arab public places, killing and maiming dozens.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] These attacks substantially increased Arab casualties and sowed terror among the population.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The first attack was on 11 November 1937, killing two Arabs at the bus depot near Jaffa Street in Jerusalem and then on 14 November, a day later commemorated as the "Day of the Breaking of the *Havlagah* (restraint)," Arabs were killed in simultaneous attacks around Palestine.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] More deadly attacks followed: on 6 July 1938 21 Arabs were killed and 52 wounded by a bomb in a Haifa market; on 25 July a second market bomb in Haifa killed at least 39 Arabs and injured 70; a bomb in Jaffa's vegetable market on 26 August killed 24 Arabs and wounded 39.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The attacks were condemned by the Jewish Agency.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The "peace bands" (*fasa'il al-salam*) or "Nashashibi units" were made up of disaffected Arab peasants recruited by the British administration and the Nashashibis in late 1938 to battle against Arab rebels during the revolt.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Despite their peasant origins the bands were representative mainly of the interests of landlords and rural notables.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Some peace bands also sprang up in the Nablus area, on Mount Carmel (a stronghold of the Druze who largely opposed the rebellion after 1937), and around Nazareth without connection to the Nashashibi-Husayni power struggle.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] From December 1937 the main opposition figures among the Arabs approached the Jewish Agency for funding and assistance, motivated by the assassination campaign pursued by the rebels at the behest of the Husseini leadership.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] From early in 1938 the Nashashibis received funding specifically to conduct anti-rebel operations, with Raghib al-Nashashibi himself receiving £5,000.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The British also supplied funding to the peace bands and sometimes directed their operations.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Fakhri Nashashibi was particularly successful in recruiting peace bands in the Hebron hills, on one occasion in December 1938 gathering 3,000 villagers for a rally in Yatta, also attended by the British military commander of the Jerusalem District General Richard O'Connor.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Just two months earlier, on 15 October 1938, rebels had seized the Old City and barricaded the gates.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] O'Connor had planned the operation by which men of the Coldstream Guards, Royal Northumberland Fusiliers and Black Watch recaptured the Old City, killing 19 rebels.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Towards the end of the revolt in May 1939 the authorities dissolved the peace bands and confiscated their arms.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] However, because members of the bands had become tainted in the eyes of the Palestinian Arabs, and some were under sentence of death, they had little choice but to continue the battle against the national movement's leadership, which they did with the continuing help of the Zionist movement.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] At least 282 rebel leaders took part in the Arab Revolt, including four Christians.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Rebel forces consisted of loosely organized bands known as *fasa'il* (sing: *fasil*).
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The leader of a *fasil* was known as a *qa'id al-fasil* (pl.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] *quwwa'id al-fasa'il*), which means "band commander".
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Jewish press often referred to them as "brigands", while the British authorities and media called them "bandits", "terrorists", "rebels" or "insurgents", but never "nationalists".
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] *Ursabat* (meaning "gangs") was another Arabic term used for the rebels, and it spawned the British soldiers' nickname for all rebels, which was *Oozlebart*.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] According to historian Simon Anglim, the rebel groups were divided into general categories: *mujahadeen* and *fedayeen*.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The former were guerrillas who engaged in armed confrontations, while the latter committed acts of sabotage.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] According to later accounts of some surviving rebel leaders from the Galilee, the *mujahideen* maintained little coordination with the nominal hierarchy of the revolt.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Most ambushes were the result of a local initiative undertaken by a *qa'id* or a group of *quwwa'id* from the same area.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Abdul Khallik was an effective peasant leader appointed by Fawzi al-Qawuqji who caused great damage and loss of life in the Nazareth District and was thus a significant adversary of the Mandate and Jewish settlement authorities.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He was trapped by British troops in a major engagement on 2 October 1938 and was killed whilst trying to lead his men to safety.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Abu Ibrahim al-Kabir was the main Qassamite rebel leader in the Upper Galilee and was the only active rebel leader on the ground who was a member of the Damascus-based Central Committee of National Jihad.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Abdallah al-Asbah was a prominent commander active in the Safad region of northeastern Galilee.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He was killed by British forces who besieged him and his comrades near the border with Lebanon in early 1937.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Abd al-Rahim al-Hajj Muhammad from the Tulkarm area was a deeply religious, intellectual man and as a fervent anti-Zionist, he was deeply committed to the revolt.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He was regarded second to Qawukji in terms of leadership ability and maintained his independence from the exiled rebel leadership in Damascus.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He personally led his *fasa'il* and carried out nighttime attacks against British targets in the revolt's early stage in 1936.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] When the revolt was renewed in April 1937, he established a more organised command hierarchy consisting of four main brigades who operated in the north-central highlands (Tulkarm–Nablus–Jenin area).
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He competed for the position of General Commander of the Revolt with Aref Abdul Razzik, and the two served the post in rotation from September 1938 to February 1939, when al-Hajj Muhammad was confirmed as the sole General Commander.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Yusuf Abu Durra, a Qassamite leader in the Jenin area, was born in Silat al-Harithiya and before becoming a rebel worked as a Gazoz vendor.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He was said to be a narrow-minded man who thrived on extortion and cruelty and thus became greatly feared.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Yusuf Hamdan was Durra's more respected lieutenant and later a leader of his own unit; he was killed by an army patrol in 1939 and buried in al-Lajjun.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Durra himself was apprehended by the Arab Legion in Transjordan on 25 July 1939 and subsequently hanged.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Fakhri Abdul Hadi of Arrabah worked closely with Fawzi al-Qawukji in 1936, but later defected to the British authorities.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He bargained for a pardon by offering to collaborate with the British on countering rebel propaganda.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Once on the payroll of the British consul in Damascus, Gilbert Mackereth, he carried out many attacks against the rebels in 1938–1939 as leader of his own "peace band".
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Aref Abdul Razzik of Tayibe was responsible for the area south of Tulkarm and was known for evading capture whilst being pursued by the security forces.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He signed his bulletins as 'The Ghost of Sheikh Qassam'.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Razzik assumed a place in British army folklore and the troops sang a song about him.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Razzik was capable and daring and gained a reputation as one of the army's problem heroes.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Issa Battat was a peasant leader in the southern hills below Jerusalem who caused enormous damage to security patrols in his area.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] He was killed by a patrol of armed police in a battle near Hebron in 1937.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In the first phase of the revolt, around 300 volunteers, mostly veterans of the Ottoman Army and/or rebels from the Great Syrian Revolt (1925–1927), deployed in northern Palestine.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Their overall commander was Fawzi al-Qawuqji and his deputies were Said al-As and Muhammad al-Ashmar.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Qawuqji also led the volunteer force's Iraqi and Transjordanian battalions, and al-Ashmar was commander of the Syrian battalion, which largely consisted of volunteers from Damascus's al-Midan Quarter, Hama and Homs.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Druze ex-Ottoman officer, Hamad Sa'ab, commanded the Lebanese battalion.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In the contest of wills between the British Empire and Palestinian aspirants for statehood, the respective efforts to secure the financial means to sustain the hostilities also played out as a battle for funding.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Mandatory Authority's repression of the revolt was bankrolled directly from London and through the revenue stream supplied to the administration by land and property taxes, stamp duties, excises on manufactured goods and customs duties on imports and exports.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Draconian collective punishment fines on the peasantry –many heavily burdened already by debt and unable to pay them – were such that revenue extracted from punitive fines exceeded, and more than compensated for, the revenue lost during the revolt.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The majority of funds raised to finance the uprising came from Arab/Muslim sources.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In the broader Arab/Muslim world a measure of financial aid, never vast, filtered in from Egypt, Syria, Iraq and Muslim India for some time.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In Palestine, the peasantry, often debt-ridden, could offer little towards subsidising the resistance.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The AHC's functions in this capacity were truncated when it was abolished by the British authorities in October 1937.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Displaced in Damascus, its leaders were cut off from contact with field units and donations gradually dried up. al-Husayni, by then in exile, proved unable to raise money, and in Syria militant contacts were informed by July 1938 that they would have to make do on their own.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] By 1938 the drop in revenues caused militant gangs to resort to extortion and robbery, often draining villages of ready cash reserves set aside to pay government fines, which then had to be met by the sale of crops and livestock.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Some contributions were obtained from American sources.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] A great deal of speculation later arose around the purported role of Germany and Italy in backing the revolt financially, based on early claims by Jewish operatives that both countries were fomenting the uprising by funneling cash and weapons to the insurgents.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] German plans to ship arms to the rebels were never implemented due to distrust of the Saudi middlemen.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Italian attempts to furnish arms by the same venue were thwarted by British intelligence.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The British never found arms or munitions of German or Italian provenance.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The rebels utilized the Italian funding to smuggle weapons into Palestine via Syria.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Total Italian funding amounted to approximately £150.000.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] It stopped in late 1938 and played no decisive role since the uprising peaked after that date.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In the first years after 1933 Germany was approached by a variety of Arab nationalist groups from Palestine and abroad asking for aid, but Germany categorically refused.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Maintaining good relations with the British was still considered to be of the uppermost priority, hence it limited itself to expressing its sympathy and moral support.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Soon after the outbreak of the revolt, in December 1936, Germany was approached by the rebel commander Fawzi al-Qawuqji and in January 1937 by representatives of the Arab Higher Committee, both requesting arms and money, but again in vain.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In July al-Husayni himself approached Walter Döhle, new German general consul in Jerusalem, to request support for the "battle against the Jews".
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Döhle found that Germany's hesitation in supporting the rebels had caused pro-German sentiment among Palestinian Arabs to waver.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Some limited German funding for the revolt can be dated to around the summer of 1938 and was perhaps related to a goal of distracting the British from the on-going occupation of Czechoslovakia.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Abwehr gave money to al-Husayni and other sums were funneled via Saudi Arabia.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Despite the intervention of up to 50,000 British troops and 15,000 Haganah men, the uprising continued for over three years.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] By the time it concluded in September 1939, more than 5,000 Arabs, over 300 Jews, and 262 Britons had been killed and at least 15,000 Arabs were wounded.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In the overall context of the Jewish settlement's development in the 1930s the physical losses endured during the revolt were relatively insignificant.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Although hundreds were killed and property was damaged no Jewish settlement was captured or destroyed and several dozen new ones were established.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Over 50,000 new Jewish immigrants arrived in Palestine.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In 1936 Jews made up about one-third of the population.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The hostilities contributed to further disengagement of the Jewish and Arab economies in Palestine, which were intertwined to some extent until that time.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Development of the economy and infrastructure accelerated.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The settlement's transportation capabilities were enhanced and Jewish unemployment was relieved owing to the employment of police officers, and replacement of striking Arab labourers, employees, craftsman and farmers by Jewish workers.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Most of the important industries in Palestine were owned by Jews and in trade and the banking sector they were much better placed than the Arabs.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] As a result of collaboration with the British colonial authorities and security forces many thousands of young men had their first experience of military training, which Moshe Shertok and Haganah leader Eliyahu Golomb cited as one of the fruits of the Haganah's policy of havlagah (restraint).
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Britain published the White Paper of 1939, a policy paper that restricted Jewish immigration and land acquisition.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Although the Jewish settlement in Palestine was dismayed by the white paper, David Ben-Gurion remained undeterred, believing that the policy would not be implemented, and in fact Neville Chamberlain had told him that the policy would last at the very most only for the duration of the war.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In the event the White Paper quotas were exhausted only in December 1944, over five and a half years later, and in the same period the United Kingdom absorbed 50,000 Jewish refugees and the British Commonwealth (Australia, Canada and South Africa) took many thousands more.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] During the War over 30,000 Jews joined the British forces and even the Irgun ceased operations against the British until 1944.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The revolt weakened the military strength of Palestinian Arabs in advance of their ultimate confrontation with the Jewish settlement in the 1947–48 Civil War in Mandatory Palestine and was, according to Benny Morris, thus counterproductive.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] During the uprising, British authorities attempted to confiscate all weapons from the Arab population.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] This, and the destruction of the main Arab political leadership in the revolt, greatly hindered their military efforts in the 1948 Palestine war, where imbalances between the Jewish and Arab economic performance, social cohesion, political organisation and military capability became apparent.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The Mufti, Hajj Amin al-Husseini and his supporters directed a Jihad against any person who did not obey the Mufti.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Their national struggle was a religious holy war, and the incarnation of both the Palestinian Arab nation and Islam was Hajj Amin al-Husseini.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Anyone who rejected his leadership was a heretic and his life was forfeit.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] After the Peel report publication, the murders of Arabs leaders who opposed the Mufti were accelerated.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Pressed by the assassination campaign pursued by the rebels at the behest of the Husseini leadership, the opposition had a security cooperation with the Jews.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The flight of wealthy Arabs, which occurred during the revolt, was also replicated in 1947–49.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Thousands of Palestinian houses were destroyed, and massive financial costs were incurred because of the general strike and the devastation of fields, crops and orchards.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The economic boycott further damaged the fragile Palestinian Arab economy through loss of sales and goods and increased unemployment.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] The new policy was regarded by many as incompatible with the commitment to a Jewish National Home in Palestine, as proclaimed in the 1917 Balfour Declaration.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Al-Husseini rejected it, although it seems that this reaction was the reverse of that of the ordinary Palestinian Arab.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] His biographer, Philip Mattar wrote that in that case, the Mufti preferred his personal interests and the ideology rather than the practical considerations.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] In February 1939 Secretary of State for Dominion Affairs Malcolm MacDonald called together a conference of Arab and Zionist leaders on the future of Palestine at St.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] James's Palace in London but the discussions ended without agreement on 27 March.The government's new policy as published in White Paper of 17 May had been determined already and despite Jewish protests and Irgun attacks the British remained resolute.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] There was a growing feeling among British officials that there was nothing left for them to do in Palestine.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Perhaps the ultimate achievement of the Arab Revolt was to make the British sick of Palestine.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] Major-General Bernard "Monty" Montgomery concluded, "the Jew murders the Arab and the Arab murders the Jew.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p02] This is what is going on in Palestine now.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] In 2003, Ted Swedenburg argued that 1936–1939 Arab Revolt has been and still is marginalized in both Western and Israeli historiography on Palestine, and even progressive Western scholars have little to say about the anti-colonial struggle of the Palestinian Arab rebels against the British Empire.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] According to Swedenburg's analysis, for instance, the Zionist version of Israeli history acknowledges only one authentic national movement: the struggle for Jewish self-determination that resulted in the Israeli Declaration of Independence in May 1948.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] Swedenburg writes that the Zionist narrative has no room for an anticolonial and anti-British Palestinian national revolt.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] Zionists often describe the revolt as a series of "events" (Hebrew מאורעות תרצ"ו-תרצ"ט) "riots", or "happenings".
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] The appropriate description was debated by Jewish Agency officials, who were keen not to give a negative impression of Palestine to prospective immigrants In private, however, David Ben-Gurion was unequivocal: the Arabs, he said, were "fighting dispossession ...
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] He concludes that it was the "Palestine surge"—that is, London's use of sheer weight of numbers to overwhelm and crush the Arab rebels—was a success.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] Matthew Hughes, a leading authority on the Revolt, notes that it is a standard move in British historiography to contrast the relative mildness of British counter-insurgency achievements with those of other Western colonial powers.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] A contrast is frequently drawn between the German suppression of the Herero, Belgium's genocide in the Congo and France's violence in Algeria to the winning-the-hearts-and-minds approach Britain is said to have adopted in Kenya in containing the Mau Mau revolt.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] One British military commander asserted that "If the Germans were in occupation in Haifa we'd not have any bloody troubles from the Arabs." Nonetheless, while moderating forces did mitigate the violence, atrocities were committed, torture used, brutality commonplace.
[src:british-empire/1936-39-arab-revolt-in-palestine-p03] Collective punishment, the razing of villages, the smashing of personal property in homes, and the destruction of foodstocks was widespread.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] A general election was held in the United Kingdom on Thursday 5 July 1945.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] With the ongoing Second World War still fresh in the minds of voters, the opposition Labour Party led by Clement Attlee won a landslide victory with a majority of 146 seats, defeating the incumbent Conservative-led government under Prime Minister Winston Churchill.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The result reflected widespread public concern about the future direction of the United Kingdom in the post-war period.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The election's campaigning was focused on leadership of the country and its postwar future.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Opinion polls when the election was called showed strong approval ratings for Churchill, but Labour had held a lead in voting intention polls since 1943.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour won a landslide victory, gaining 239 seats for a total majority of 146 with 49.7% of the popular vote, allowing Attlee to become prime minister.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The party also won two seats in a walkover, the last time any seat in the House of Commons went uncontested in a general election.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] This was Labour's first outright majority and enabled Attlee to begin implementing the party's post-war reforms.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The result was a major shock for the Conservatives, who lost 189 seats despite winning 36.2% of the vote, having campaigned on the assumption that Churchill's wartime leadership would secure victory.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Party suffered a net loss of nine seats and its leader Archibald Sinclair lost his seat, while the Liberal National Party lost 22 seats, including that of its leader Ernest Brown.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] A total of 324 new MPs entered the House of Commons, a record that stood until 2024.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Additionally, the beginning of the Attlee ministry paralleled the beginning of the Truman administration in the United States.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The 11.7% swing from the Conservatives to an opposition party is the largest since the Acts of Union 1800; the Conservative loss of the vote exceeded that of the 1906 Liberal landslide ousting of a Conservative administration.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] It was also the first election since 1906 in which the Conservatives did not win a plurality (relative majority) of the popular vote.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Churchill remained actively involved in politics and returned as prime minister after leading his party into the 1951 general election.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] For the Liberal National Party the election was their last as a distinct party, as they merged with the Conservatives in 1947 (although they operated as a subsidiary party of the Conservatives until 1968) while Ernest Brown resigned from politics in the aftermath of the election.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Held less than two months following VE Day, this was the first general election since 1935, as general elections had been suspended by Parliament during the Second World War.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Clement Attlee, the leader of the Labour Party, refused Winston Churchill's offer of continuing the wartime coalition until the Allied defeat of Japan.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] On 15 June, King George VI dissolved Parliament, which had been sitting for nearly ten years without an election.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Labour manifesto, *Let Us Face the Future*, included promises of nationalisation, economic planning, full employment, a National Health Service, and a system of social security.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The manifesto proved popular with the electorate, selling one and a half million copies.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Churchill's Declaration to the Voters*, on the other hand, included progressive ideas on key social issues but was relatively vague on the idea of postwar economic control, and the party was associated with high levels of unemployment in the 1930s.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] It failed to convince voters that it could effectively deal with unemployment in a postwar Britain.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] In May 1945, when the war in Europe ended, Churchill's approval ratings stood at 83%, but the Labour Party had held an 18% poll lead as of February 1945.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The polls for some seats were delayed until 12 July and in Nelson and Colne until 19 July because of local wakes weeks.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The results were counted and declared on 26 July to allow time to transport the votes of those serving overseas.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Victory over Japan Day ensued on 15 August.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The caretaker government, led by Churchill, was heavily defeated.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Labour Party led by Attlee won a landslide victory and gained a majority of 146 seats.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] It was the first election in which Labour gained a majority of seats and the first in which it won a relative majority (plurality) of votes.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was a disaster for the Liberal Party, which lost all of its urban seats, and marked its transition from being a party of government to a party of the political fringe.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Its leader, Archibald Sinclair, lost his rural seat of Caithness and Sutherland.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] That was the last general election until 2019 in which a major party leader lost their seat, but Sinclair lost only by six votes in a very tight three-way contest.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal National Party fared even worse by losing two-thirds of its seats and falling behind the Liberals in seat count for the first time since the parties split in 1931.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] It was the final election that the Liberal Nationals fought as an autonomous party, as they merged with the Conservative Party two years later although they continued to exist as a subsidiary party of the Conservatives until 1968.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Future prominent figures who entered Parliament included Harold Wilson, James Callaghan, Barbara Castle, Michael Foot and Hugh Gaitskell.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Future Conservative Prime Minister Harold Macmillan lost his seat, but he returned to Parliament at a by-election later that year.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The greatest factor in Labour's dramatic win appeared to be its policy of social reform.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] In one opinion poll, 41% of respondents considered housing to be the most important issue that faced the country, 15% stated the Labour policy of full employment, 7% mentioned social security, 6% nationalisation, and just 5% international security, which was emphasised by the Conservatives.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Beveridge Report, published in 1942, proposed the creation of a welfare state.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] It called for a dramatic turn in British social policy, with provision for nationalised healthcare, expansion of state-funded education, National Insurance and a new housing policy.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The report was extremely popular, and copies of its findings were widely purchased, turning it into a best-seller.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Labour Party adopted the report eagerly, and the Conservatives (including Churchill, who did not regard the reforms as socialist) accepted many of the principles of the report, but claimed that they were not affordable.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour offered a new comprehensive welfare policy, reflecting a consensus that social changes were needed.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives were not willing to make the same changes that Labour proposed, and appeared out of step with public opinion.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour played to the concept of "winning the peace" that would follow the war.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Possibly for that reason, there was especially strong support for Labour in the armed services, which feared the unemployment and homelessness to which the soldiers of the First World War had returned.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] It has been claimed that the left-wing bias of teachers in the armed services was a contributing factor, but that argument has generally not carried much weight, and the failure of the Conservative governments in the 1920s to deliver a "land fit for heroes" was likely more important.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour had also been given during the war the opportunity to display to the electorate its domestic competence in government, under men such as Attlee as Deputy Prime Minister, Herbert Morrison at the Home Office and Ernest Bevin at the Ministry of Labour.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The differing wartime strategies of the two parties likewise gave Labour an advantage.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour continued to attack prewar Conservative governments for their inactivity in tackling Hitler, reviving the economy and rearming Britain, but Churchill was less interested in furthering his party, much to the chagrin of many of its members and MPs.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Though voters respected and liked Churchill's wartime record, they were more distrustful of the Conservative Party's domestic and foreign policy record in the late 1930s.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Churchill and the Conservatives are also generally considered to have run a poor campaign in comparison to Labour.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Churchill's personal popularity remained high; hence, the Conservatives were confident of victory and based much of their election campaign on that, rather than proposing new programmes.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] However, people distinguished between Churchill and his party, a contrast that Labour repeatedly emphasised throughout the campaign.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Voters also harboured doubts over Churchill's ability to lead the country on the domestic front.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The writer and soldier Anthony Burgess remarked that Churchill, who then often wore a colonel's uniform, was not nearly as popular with soldiers at the front as with officers and civilians.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Burgess noted that Churchill often smoked cigars in front of soldiers who had not had a decent cigarette in days.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] In addition to the poor Conservative general election strategy, Churchill went so far as to accuse Attlee of seeking to behave as a dictator, despite Attlee's service as part of Churchill's war cabinet.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] In the most famous incident of the campaign, Churchill's first election broadcast on 4 June backfired dramatically and memorably.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Denouncing his former coalition partners, he declared that Labour "would have to fall back on some form of a Gestapo" to impose socialism on Britain.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Attlee responded the next night by ironically thanking the prime minister for demonstrating to the people the difference between "Churchill the great wartime leader" and "Churchill the peacetime politician" and argued the case for public control of industry.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Another blow to the Conservative campaign was the memory of the 1930s policy of appeasement, conducted by Churchill's Conservative predecessors, Neville Chamberlain and Stanley Baldwin, that had been widely discredited for allowing Adolf Hitler's Germany to become too powerful.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour had strongly advocated appeasement until 1938, but the interwar period had been dominated by Conservatives.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] With the exception of two brief minority Labour governments in 1924 and 1929–1931, the Conservatives had been in power for all of the interwar period.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] As a result, the Conservatives were generally blamed for the era's mistakes: appeasement, inflation and the unemployment of the Great Depression.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Many voters felt that although the First World War had been won, the peace that followed had been lost.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] All comparisons are with the winning party in the 1935 election; the aim is to provide a comparison with the previous general election.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] This list includes seats where the incumbent was standing down and therefore there was no possibility of a particular person being defeated.
[src:british-empire/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Polls showed a lead for Labour since 1943, except for one poll in June 1945 when both Labour and the Conservatives tied on 45%.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] It broke out after the General Assembly of the United Nations adopted a resolution on 29 November 1947 recommending the adoption of the Partition Plan for Palestine.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] During the civil war, Palestine's Jewish and Arab communities clashed (the latter supported by the Arab Liberation Army) while the British, who had the obligation to maintain order, organized their withdrawal and intervened only occasionally.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] This offensive greatly accelerated the 1948 Palestinian expulsion and flight, which was effected by various violent means, including a number of massacres such as the widely publicized Deir Yassin massacre.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The conflict thus escalated and became the 1948 Arab–Israeli War.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Under the control of a British administration since 1920, Palestine found itself the object of a battle between Palestinian and Zionist nationalists, groups that opposed both the British mandate and each other.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Britain also reduced Jewish immigration in response to the violence, as legislated by the 1939 White Paper.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] After World War II and The Holocaust, the Zionist movement gained attention and sympathy.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In Mandatory Palestine, Zionist groups fought against the British administration.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In the two and a half years from 1945 to June 1947, British law enforcement forces lost 103 dead and sustained 391 wounded by Jewish militants.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Palestinian Arab nationalists reorganized, but their organization remained inferior to the Zionists'.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 15 August 1947, the Haganah blew up the house of a Palestinian family near Petah Tikva, killing 12 occupants, including a woman and six children.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] After November 1947, the dynamiting of houses formed a key component of most Haganah strikes.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Diplomacy failed to reconcile the different points of view on Palestine's future.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In early November, the Haganah began mobilizing for war, and issued an order that all men between 17 and 25 register.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 18 February 1947, the British announced their withdrawal from the region and on 29 November, the General Assembly of the United Nations voted to recommend the adoption and implementation of the partition plan with the support of the big global powers, though the Arab states opposed it.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] A "wind of violence" took hold of the country, foreboding civil war between the two communities.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Murders, reprisals, and counter-reprisals resulted in dozens killed on both sides in the process.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The impasse persisted as British forces did not intervene to stop the violence.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The first casualties after the adoption of Resolution 181(II) were passengers on a Jewish bus near Kfar Sirkin on 30 November, after an eight-man gang from Jaffa ambushed the bus killing five and wounding others.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Half an hour later they ambushed a second bus, southbound from Hadera, killing two more, and shots were fired at Jewish buses in Jerusalem and Haifa.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] This was said to be a retaliation for the Shubaki family assassination, the killing ten days earlier of five Palestinian Arabs by Lehi near Herzliya.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Irgun and Lehi (the latter also known as the Stern Gang) followed their strategy of placing bombs in crowded markets and bus stops.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 30 December, in Haifa, members of the Irgun threw two bombs at a crowd of Arab workers who were queueing in front of a refinery, killing 6 and injuring 42.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] An angry crowd massacred 39 Jewish people in revenge until British soldiers reestablished calm.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In reprisal, soldiers from the Palmach and the Carmeli brigade attacked the villages of Balad ash-Sheikh and Hawassa.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In what became known as the Balad al-Shaykh massacre, between 60 and 70 villagers were killed.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In early 1948, forces under the command of Abd al-Qadir al-Husayni set up a blockade of Jerusalem, with its 100,000 Jewish residents.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] To counter this, the Yishuv authorities tried to supply the city with convoys of up to 100 armoured vehicles, but the operation became increasingly impractical as casualties in the relief convoys surged.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] By March, Al-Husayni's tactic had paid off.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Almost all the Haganah's armoured vehicles had been destroyed, the blockade was in full operation, and hundreds of Haganah members who had tried to bring supplies into the city were killed.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The situation for those who dwelt in the Jewish settlements in the highly isolated Negev and North of Galilee was even more critical.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] From January onward, operations became increasingly militarized.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In all the mixed zones where both communities lived, particularly Jerusalem and Haifa, there were increasingly violent attacks, riots, reprisals and counter-reprisals.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Isolated shootings evolved into all-out battles.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Attacks against traffic, for instance, turned into ambushes as one bloody attack led to another.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 22 February 1948, supporters of Mohammad Amin al-Husayni, with the help of certain British deserters, organized three attacks against the Jewish community.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Using car bombs aimed at the headquarters of the Zionist *Palestine Post* newspaper, the Ben Yehuda St. market, and the backyard of the Jewish Agency's offices, they killed 22, 53, and 13 Jews respectively, a total of 88 fatalities.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In retaliation, Lehi put a landmine on the railroad track in Rehovot on which a train from Cairo to Haifa was travelling, killing 28 British soldiers and injuring 35.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] This was copied on 31 March, close to Caesarea Maritima, which led to the death of 40 people and injured 60, mostly Arab civilians.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] David Ben-Gurion reorganized the Haganah and made conscription obligatory.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Every Jew in the country had to receive military training.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] This situation caused the United States to withdraw its support for the partition plan and instead propose a trusteeship for Palestine in March 1948, thus encouraging the Arab League to believe that the Palestinian Arabs, reinforced by the Arab Liberation Army, could quash the partition plan.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The British, on the other hand, decided on 7 February 1948 to support Transjordan's annexation of the Arab part of Palestine.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] While the Jewish population had received strict orders requiring it to hold its ground everywhere at all costs, the Arab population was more affected by the general conditions of insecurity to which the country was exposed.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Up to 100,000 Arabs, from the urban upper and middle classes in Haifa, Jaffa and Jerusalem, or Jewish-dominated areas, evacuated abroad or to Arab centres eastwards.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] As a consequence of funds raised by Golda Meir from sympathisers in the United States, and Stalin's decision to support the Zionist cause, the Jewish representatives of Palestine were able to sign very important armament contracts in the East.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Other Haganah agents recovered stockpiles from World War II, which helped improve the army's equipment and logistics.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The Jewish Agency had set aside $28 million for foreign arms purchases alone.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] By comparison, the Arab Higher Committee's total budget at this time amounted to $2,250,000, equivalent to the Haganah's annual budget in prewar times.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Several Arab Liberation Army regiments intervened in Palestine, each active in a variety of distinct sectors around the different coastal towns.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] They consolidated their presence in Galilee and Samaria.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Abd al-Qadir al-Husayni came from Egypt with several hundred men of the Army of the Holy War.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] German and Bosnian WWII veterans, including a handful of former intelligence, Wehrmacht, and Waffen SS officers, were among the volunteers fighting for the Palestinian cause.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In addition, roughly 100 to 200 British soldiers and police officers, many of whom had developed bitterness towards the Zionist movement and/or pity for the Palestinians over the course of the British counterinsurgency campaign against the Zionists, deserted to help the Palestinians.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In contrast, only 17 deserters fought for the Yishuv.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Benny Morris writes that the Yishuv was more successful in attracting and effectively deploying foreign military professionals than its Arab adversaries.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] He concludes that the ex-Nazis and Bosnian Muslims recruited by the Palestinians, Egyptians, and Syrians "proved of little significance" to the outcome of the conflict.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In December 1947, the Jewish death toll was estimated at over 200, and, according to Alec Kirkbride, by 18 January 1948, 333 Jews and 345 Arabs had been killed while 643 Jews and 877 Arabs had been injured.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The overall death toll between December 1947 and January 1948 (including British personnel) was estimated at 1,000 people, with 2,000 injured.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Ilan Pappé estimates that 400 Jews and 1,500 Arabs were killed by January 1948.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Morris says that by the end of March 1948, the Yishuv had suffered about a thousand dead.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] According to Yoav Gelber, by the end of March, 2,000 were dead and 4,000 wounded.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] These figures correspond to an average of more than 100 deaths and 200 casualties per week among a population of 2,000,000.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Violence kept intensifying with the intervention of military units.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Although responsible for law and order up until the end of the mandate, the British did not try to take control of the situation, being more involved in the liquidation of the administration and the evacuation of their troops.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Furthermore, the authorities felt that they had lost enough men already in the conflict.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The British either could not or did not want to impede the intervention of foreign forces into Palestine.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Fawzi al-Qawuqji, Field Commander of the Arab Liberation Army, arrived, according to his own account, on 4 March, with the rest of the logistics and around 100 Bosniak volunteers in Jab'a, a small village on the route between Nablus and Jenin.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] He established a headquarters there and a training centre for Palestinian Arab volunteers.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In March, an Iraqi regiment of the Arab Liberation Army came to reinforce the Palestinian Arab troops of Salameh in the area around Lydda and Ramleh, while Al-Husayni started a headquarters in Bir Zeit, 10 km to the north of Ramallah.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] At the same time, a number of North African troops, principally Libyans, and hundreds of members of the Muslim Brotherhood entered Palestine.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In March, an initial regiment arrived in Gaza and certain militants among them reached Jaffa.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The Arab combatants' initial victories reinforced morale among them.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The Arab Higher Committee was confident and decided to prevent the set-up of the UN-backed partition plan.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The situation of the 100,000 Jews situated in Jerusalem was precarious, and supplies to the city, already slim in number, were likely to be stopped.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Nonetheless, despite the setbacks suffered, the Jewish forces, in particular Haganah, remained superior in number and quality to those of the Arab forces.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The high morale of the Arab fighters and politicians was not shared by the Palestinian Arab civilian population.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The UN Palestine Commission reported 'Panic continues to increase, however, throughout the Arab middle classes, and there is a steady exodus of those who can afford to leave the country.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] 'From December 1947 to January 1948, around 70,000 Arabs fled, and, by the end of March, that number had grown to around 100,000.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] These people were part of the first wave of Palestinian refugees of the conflict.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Mostly the middle and upper classes fled, including the majority of the families of local governors and representatives of the Arab Higher Committee.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Non-Palestinian Arabs also fled in large numbers.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Most of them did not abandon the hope of returning to Palestine once the hostilities had ended.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Many decisions were made abroad that had an important influence over the outcome of the conflict.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Britain did not want a Palestinian state led by the Mufti, and opted unofficially instead, on 7 February 1948, to support the annexation of the Arab part of Palestine by Abdullah I of Transjordan.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] They held that the Arab Legion not enter the vicinity of Jerusalem or the Jewish state itself.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] This option did not envisage a Palestinian Arab state.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Although the ambitions of King Abdullah are known, it is not apparent to what extent the authorities of Yishuv, the Arab Higher Committee or the Arab League knew of this decision.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The US suggested that Palestine instead be put under UN supervision.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 1 April, the UN Security Council voted on the US proposal to convoke a special assembly to reconsider the Palestinian problem; the Soviet Union abstained.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] This U-turn by the US caused concern and debate among Yishuv authorities.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] They thought that after the withdrawal of British troops, the Yishuv could not effectively resist the Arab forces without the support of the US.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In this context, Elie Sasson, the director of the Arab section of Jewish Agency, and several other personalities, persuaded David Ben-Gurion and Golda Meyerson to advance a diplomatic initiative to the Arabs.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] However, Syria also bought arms from Czechoslovakia for the Arab Liberation Army, but the shipment never arrived due to Haganah intervention.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Possible motivations for Stalin's decision include his support of the UN Partition plan, and allowing Czechoslovakia to earn some foreign income after being forced to refuse Marshall Plan assistance.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The extent of this support and the concrete role that it played is up for debate.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Figures advanced by historians tend to vary.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In any case, the embargo that was extended to all Arab states in May 1948 by the UN Security Council caused great problems to them.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Arab leaders did what they could to avoid being directly involved in support for the Palestinian cause.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] At the Arab League summit of October 1947, in Aley, the Iraqi general, Ismail Safwat, painted a realist picture of the situation.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] He underlined the better organization and greater financial support of the Jewish people in comparison to the Palestinians.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] He recommended the immediate deployment of the Arab armies at the Palestinian borders, the dispatching of weapons and ammunition to the Palestinians, and the contribution of a million pounds of financial aid to them.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] His proposals were rejected, other than the suggestion to send financial support, which was not followed up on.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Nonetheless, a techno-military committee was established to coordinate assistance to the Palestinians.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Based in Cairo, it was directed by Safwat, who was supported by Lebanese and Syrian officers and representatives of the Higher Arab Committee.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] A Transjordian delegate was also appointed, but he did not participate in meetings.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] At the December 1947 Cairo summit, under pressure by public opinion, the Arab leaders decided to create a military command that united all the heads of all the major Arab states, headed by Safwat.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] They still ignored his calls for financial and military aid, preferring to defer any decision until the end of the Mandate, but, nevertheless, decide to form the Arab Liberation Army, which would go into action in the following weeks.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On the night of 20–21 January 1948, around 700 armed Syrians entered Palestine via Transjordan.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In February 1948, Safwat reiterated his demands, but they fell on deaf ears: the Arab governments hoped that the Palestinians, aided by the Arab Liberation Army, could manage on their own until the International community renounced the partition plan.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The Arab Liberation Army was, in theory, financed and equipped by the Arab League.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] A budget of one million pounds sterling had been promised to them, due to the insistence of Ismail Safwat.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In reality, though, funding never arrived, and only Syria truly supported the Arab volunteers in concrete terms.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Syria bought from Czechoslovakia a quantity of arms for the Arab Liberation Army but the shipment never arrived due to Hagana force intervention.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] According to Lapierre & Collins, on the ground, logistics were completely neglected, and their leader, Fawzi al-Qawuqji, envisaged that his troops survive only on the expenses accorded to them by the Palestinian population.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] However, Gelber says that the Arab League had arranged the supplies through special contractors.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] They were equipped with different types of light weapons, light and medium-sized mortars, a number of 75 mm and 105 mm guns, and armoured vehicles but their stock of shells was small.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The situation that the Army of the Holy War and the Palestinian forces were in was worse.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] They could not rely on any form of foreign support and had to get by on the funds that Mohammad Amin al-Husayni could raise.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The troops' armament was limited to what the fighters already had.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] To make things even worse, they had to be content with arms bought on the black market or pillaged from British warehouses, and, as a result, did not really have enough arms to wage war.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Until March, Haganah suffered also a lack of arms.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The Jewish fighters benefitted from a number of clandestine factories that manufactured some light weapons, ammunition and explosives.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The one weapon of which there was no shortage was locally produced explosives.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] However, they had far less than what was necessary to carry out a war: in November, only one out of every three Jewish combatants was armed, rising to two out of three within Palmach.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Haganah sent agents to Europe and to the United States, in order to arm and equip this army.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] To finance all of this, Golda Meir managed, by the end of December, to collect $25 million through a fundraising campaign set about in the United States to capitalize on American sympathisers to the Zionist cause.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Out of the 129 million US dollars raised between October 1947 and March 1949 for the Zionist cause, more than $78 million, over 60%, were used to buy arms and munition.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] A leased transport plane was used for the Operation Balak first arms ferry flight from Czechoslovakia on the end of March 1948.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] At the beginning of April 1948, a shipment of thousands of rifles and hundreds of machine guns arrived at Tel Aviv harbor.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] With this big shipment, Haganah could supply weapons to a concentrated effort, without taking over the arms of other Jewish territory and risking them being with no weapons.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Haganah went into the offensive, although still lacking heavy weapons.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] After 'having gotten the Jews of Palestine and of elsewhere to do everything that they could, personally and financially, to help Yishuv,' Ben-Gurion's second greatest achievement was his having successfully transformed Haganah from being a clandestine paramilitary organization into a true army.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Ben-Gurion appointed Israel Galili to the position of head of the High Command counsel of Haganah and divided Haganah into 6 infantry brigades, numbered 1 to 6, allotting a precise theatre of operation to each one.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Yigael Yadin assumed the responsibility on the ground as chief of Operations.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Palmach, commanded by Yigal Allon, was divided into 3 elite brigades, numbered 10–12, and constituted the mobile force of Haganah.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Ben-Gurion's attempts to retain personal control over the newly formed IDF lead later in July to The Generals' Revolt.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 19 November 1947, obligatory conscription was instituted for all men and women aged between 17 and 25.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] By end of March 21,000 people had been conscripted.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 30 March the call-up was extended to men and single women aged between 26 and 35.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Five days later a General Mobilization order was issued for all men under 40.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] "From November 1947, the Haganah, (...) began to change from a territorial militia into a regular army.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] (...) Few of the units had been well trained by December.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] (...) By March–April, it fielded still under-equipped battalion and brigades.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Apart from on the coastline, Jewish yishuvim, or settlements, were very dispersed.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Communication between the coastal area (the main area of Jewish settlements) and the peripheral settlements was by road.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] These road were an easy target for attacks, as most of them passed through or near entirely Arab localities.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The possibility of evacuating these difficult to defend zones was considered, but the policy of Haganah was set by David Ben-Gurion.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] He stated that "what the Jewish people have has to be conserved.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] No Jewish person should abandon his or her house, farm, kibbutz or job without authorization.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Every outpost, every colony, whether it is isolated or not, must be occupied as though it were Tel Aviv itself." No Jewish settlement was evacuated until the invasion of May 1948.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Only a dozen kibbutzim in Galilee, and those in Gush Etzion sent women and children into the safer interior zones.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Ben-Gurion gave instructions that the settlements of Negev be reinforced in number of men and goods, in particular the kibbutzim of Kfar Darom and Yad Mordechai (both close to Gaza), Revivim (south of Beersheba), and Kfar Etzion.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Conscious of the danger that weighed upon Negev, the supreme command of Haganah assigned a whole Palmach battalion there.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Jerusalem and the great difficulty of accessing the city became even more critical to its Jewish population, who made up one sixth of the total Jewish population in Palestine.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The long and difficult route from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem, after leaving the Jewish zone at Hulda, went through the foothills of Latrun.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The 28-kilometre route between Bab al-Wad and Jerusalem took no less than three hours, and the route passed near the Arab villages of Saris, Qaluniya, Al-Qastal, and Deir Yassin.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Abd al-Qadir al-Husayni arrived in Jerusalem with the intent to surround and besiege its Jewish community.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] He moved to Surif, a village to the southwest of Jerusalem, with his supporters—around a hundred fighters who were trained in Syria before the war and who served as officers in his army, Jihad al-Muqadas, or Army of the Holy War.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] He was joined by a hundred or so young villagers and Arab veterans of the British Army.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] His militia soon had several thousand men, and it moved its training quarters to Bir Zeit, a town near Ramallah.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Abd al-Qadir's zone of influence extended down to the area of Lydda, Ramleh, and the Judean Hills where Hasan Salama commanded 1,000 men.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Salama, like Abd al-Qadir, had been affiliated with Mufti Haj Amin al Husseini for years, and had also been a commander in the 1936–1939 Arab revolt in Palestine, participated in the Rashid Ali coup of 1941 and the subsequent Anglo-Iraqi War.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Salama had re-entered Palestine in 1944 in Operation Atlas, parachuting into the Jordan Valley as a member of a special German—Arab commando unit of the Waffen SS.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] He coordinated with al-Husayni to execute a plan of disruption and harassment of road traffic in an attempt to isolate and blockade Western (Jewish) Jerusalem.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 10 December, the first organized attack occurred when ten members of a convoy between Bethlehem and Kfar Etzion were killed.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 14 January, Abd al-Qadir himself commanded and took part in an attack against Kfar Etzion, in which 1,000 Palestinian Arab combatants were involved.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The attack was a failure, and 200 of al-Husayni's men died.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Nonetheless, the attack did not come without losses of Jewish lives: a detachment of 35 Palmach men who sought to reinforce the establishment were ambushed and killed.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 25 January, a Jewish convoy was attacked near the Arab village of al-Qastal.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The attack went badly and several villages to the northeast of Jerusalem answered a call for assistance, although others did not, for fear of reprisals.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The campaign for control over the roads became increasingly militaristic in nature, and became a focal point of the Arab war effort.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] After 22 March, supply convoys to Jerusalem stopped, due to a convoy of around thirty vehicles having been destroyed in the gorges of Bab-el-Wad.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 27 March, an important supply convoy from Kfar Etzion was taken in an ambush in south of Jerusalem.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] They were forced to surrender all of their arms, ammunition and vehicles to al-Husayni's forces.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The Jews of Jerusalem requested the assistance of the United Kingdom after 24 hours of combat.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] According to a British report, the situation in Jerusalem, where a food rationing system was already in application, risked becoming desperate after 15 May.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The situation in other areas of the country was as critical as the one of Jerusalem.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The settlements of Negev were utterly isolated, due to the impossibility of using the Southern coastal road, which passed through zones densely populated by Arabs.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 27 March, a convoy of supplies (the Yehiam convoy) that was intended for the isolated kibbutzim north-west of Galilee was attacked in the vicinity of Nahariya.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In the ensuing battle, 42–47 Haganah combatants and around a hundred fighters of the Arab Liberation Army were killed, and all vehicles involved were destroyed.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The second phase of the war, which began in April, marked a huge change in direction, as Haganah moved to the offensive.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In this stage, Arab forces were composed of around 10,000 men among which between 3,000 and 5,000 foreign volunteers serving in the Arab Liberation Army.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Haganah and Palmach forces were steadily increasing.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In March, they aligned around 15,000 men and in May around 30,000 who were better equipped, trained and organized.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The armed Palestinian groups were roundly defeated, Yishuv took control of some of the principal routes that linked the Jewish settlements, and as a consequence, Jerusalem was able to receive supplies again.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Many mixed cities were taken by the Haganah as well as Jaffa.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Plan Dalet was finalized on 10 March 1948, under the direction of Yigael Yadin.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] 75 pages long, it laid down the rules and the objects that were to be followed by Haganah during the second phase of the war.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Its principal objective was to secure Yishuv's uninterrupted territorial connections, particularly in response to the war of the roads carried out by Al-Husayni and in preparation for the Arab states' declared intervention.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Plan Dalet caused quite a controversy among historians.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Some see it as a plan that was primarily defensive and military in nature and a preparation against invasion, whereas others think that the plan was offensive in nature and aimed at conquering as much of Palestine as possible, or enacted with the aim of ethnically cleansing Palestine.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] At the end of March 1948, Husayni's troops prevented supply convoys from reaching Jerusalem.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The city was besieged and the Jewish population was forced to adhere to a rationing system.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Ben-Gurion decided to launch the operation Nachshon to open up the city and provide supplies to Jerusalem.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Operation Nachshon marked the Haganah shift to the offensive, even before launching plan D.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The first orders were given on 2 April 1948 with diversion attacks including Qastel.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Between 5–20 April 1500 men from the Givati and Harel brigades took control of the road to Jerusalem and allowed 3 or 4 convoys to reach the city.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] All the Arab villages that blocked the route were either taken or destroyed, and the Jewish forces were victorious in all their engagements.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Nonetheless, not all the objectives of the operation were achieved, since only 1800 tonnes of the 3,000 envisaged were transported to the city, and two months of severe rationing had to be assumed.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Abd al-Qadir al-Husayni was killed during the night of 7–8 April, in the midst of the battles taking place in Al-Qastal.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Operation Nachshon exposed the poor military organization of the Palestinian paramilitary groups.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Due to lack of logistics, particularly food and ammunition, they were incapable of maintaining engagements that were more than a few hours away from their permanent bases.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Faced with these events, the Arab Higher Committee asked Alan Cunningham to allow the return of the Mufti, the only person capable of redressing the situation.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Despite obtaining permission, the Mufti did not get to Jerusalem.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] His declining prestige cleared the way for the expansion of the influence of the Arab Liberation Army and of Fawzi Al-Qawuqji in the Jerusalem area.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] This consisted in poisoning village wells.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In the final months of the ensuing 1948 Arab-Israeli war, as Israel gained the upper hand, orders were apparently given to extend the use of biological agents against the Arab states themselves.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Mishmar HaEmek is a kibbutz that was founded by Mapam in 1930, in the Jezreel Valley, close to the road between Haifa and Jenin that passes the Megiddo kibbutz.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] It is situated in a place that Haganah officers considered to be on one of the most likely axes of penetration for a 'major Arab attack' against the Yishuv.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 4 April, the Arab Liberation Army launched an attack on the kibbutz with the support of artillery.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The attack was fought off by the members of the kibbutz, who were supported by Haganah soldiers.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The artillery fire that had almost totally destroyed the kibbutz was stopped by a British column, who arrived on the scene by order of General MacMillan, and, on 7 April, Fawzi Al-Qawuqji accepted a 24-hour ceasefire, but required that the kibbutz be surrendered.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The inhabitants of the kibbutz evacuated their children, and, after having consulted Tel Aviv, refused to surrender.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 8 or 9 April, Haganah prepared a counter-offensive.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Yitzhak Sadeh was put in charge of operations, with the order to 'clean out' the region.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Sadeh's men besieged all the villages around the kibbutz, and the Arab Liberation Army had to retreat to its bases in Jabba.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The majority of the inhabitants of the region fled, but those who did not were either imprisoned or expelled to Jenin.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The villages were plundered by some Kibbutznikim and razed to the ground with explosives with accordance to Plan Dalet.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] According to Morris, the Arab Liberation Army soldiers were demoralized by reports of the Deir Yassin massacre and the death of Abd al-Qadir al-Husayni.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Throughout battle, they had generally been forced to withdraw and to abandon the people of the villages.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] According to Morris, "according to Ben-Gurion, some 640 Haganah soldiers had faced about twenty-five hundred ALA troops, with superior firepower—and bested them".
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] When the battle finished, Palmach forces continued 'cleaning' operations until 19 April, destroying several villages and forcing those who inhabited them to flee.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Some villages were also evacuated under the instruction of Arab authorities.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In May, Irgun engaged in several operations in the region, razing a number of villages and killing some of their inhabitants, as did some detachments from the Golani and Alexandroni brigades.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Deir Yassin is a village located 5 kilometres west of Jerusalem.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 9 April 1948, independently of operation Nachshon, around 120 Irgun and Lehi men attacked the village and ran into resistance, capturing it after a fierce battle with Palmach help.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Irgun and Lehi lost 4 dead and 35 wounded.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Between 100 and 120 inhabitants of the village were killed in the attack, mostly civilians.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Haganah had approved the attack and assisted in it.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The operation led to indignation from the international community, the more so since the press of the time reported that the death toll was 254.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Ben-Gurion roundly condemned it, as did the principal Jewish authorities: the Haganah, the Great Rabbinate and the Jewish Agency for Israel, who sent a letter of condemnation, apology and condolence to King Abdullah I of Transjordan.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 13 April, partly in revenge for the Deir Yassin massacre, a convoy that was driving towards Jerusalem's Hadassah Hospital on Mount Scopus was attacked by hundreds of Arabs.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In the seven-hour battle 79 Jews were killed including doctors and patients.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Thirteen British soldiers were present, but they stood by, only putting in a perfunctory attempt at intervention in the last moments of the massacre.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Lieutenant-Colonel Jack Churchill was present at the scene, and later testified that he had attempted to assist the Hadassah convoy by radioing for support, only for the request to be turned down.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Following the 'fiasco' of Mishmar HaEmek, Fawzi Al-Qawuqji ordered the Druze regiment of the Arab Liberation Army into action, to carry out diversion operations.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Druze soldiers took position in several Arab villages 12 kilometres to the east of Haifa, whence they occasionally attacked traffic and Jewish settlements, including Ramat Yohanan.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Kibbutznikim and the Haganah soldiers that supported them forced back their attacks and razed the villages from which they launched their attacks.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Having run out of ammunition, the Druze withdrew to their base in Shefa-'Amr, with one hundred casualties.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] After an initial failure, a battalion-sized Carmeli force on the night of 15–16 April overran the two villages.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Druze Battalion, on 16 April assaulted the Carmeli positions nine times but the Carmeli troops fought back.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] By afternoon, the exhausted Druze troops retreated.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Druze had already made contact on several occasions with Yishuv agents and following their defeat at Ramat Yohanan, the Druze officers offered to defect and to join the ranks of Haganah.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] This proposition was discussed with Yigael Yadin, who refused the proposal but suggested that they could help to carry out sabotage operations behind the backs of the Arabs and to influence their comrades into deserting the army.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] By the start of May, 212 Wahab soldiers deserted.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Taking into account the attitude of his men, Wahab met with Jewish liaison officers on 9 May and agreed to cooperate with Haganah.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The two parties avoided clashes, and Wahab created a neutral enclave in the centre of Galilee.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Wahab's army did not respond to calls for it to help fight Haganah's occupation of Acre, and avoided being present while Haganah occupied the police fortress of Shefa-'Amr during its evacuation by the British.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The position that the Druze took influenced their fate after the war.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Given the good relationship between the Druze and Yishuv from 1930 onwards despite their collaboration with the Arab Higher Council and the Arab League, Ben-Gurion insisted that the Druze, as well as the Circassians and the Maronites benefit from a different position to that of the other Arabs.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In the context of Plan Dalet, mixed urban centres, or those on the borders of the Jewish state, were attacked and besieged by Jewish forces.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Tiberias was attacked on 10 April and fell six days later; Haifa fell on 23 April, after only one day of combat (Operation Bi'ur Hametz), and Jaffa was attacked on 27 April but fell only after the British abandoned it (Operation Hametz).
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Safed and Beisan (Operation Gideon) fell on 11 May and 13 May respectively, within the framework of Operation Yitfah, and Acre fell on 17 May, within the framework of Operation Ben-Ami.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Arab inhabitants of these towns fled or were expelled en masse.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In these 6 cities, only 13,000 of the total of 177,000 Arab inhabitants remained by the end of May.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] This phenomenon ricocheted also in the suburbs and the majority of the zone's Arab villages.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Despite the deteriorating situation for the Arabs, a representative of the Arab Higher Committee Representative stated to UN Security Council on April 16 that the Arabs would reject any ceasefire that does not undo the Partition plan.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Galilee Panhandle, a zone in northeastern Galilee, between the Lake Tiberias and Metula, was the Jewish-controlled area that was the most distant and isolated from the area most densely populated by Jews, the coastal plain.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The presence of the Lebanese border to the north, the Syrian border to east and the Arab presence in the rest of Galilee made it a probable target for intervention of the Arab armies.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Within the framework of the Dalet plan, Yigael Yadin entrusted Yigal Allon, commander of the Palmach, with the responsibility of managing Operation Yiftah, whose objectives were to control all the aforementioned area and consolidate it ahead of the Arab attack that was planned for 15 May.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Allon was in charge the 1st and 3rd Palmach battalions, which had to face the populace of Safed and several dozen Arab villages.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The situation was made more problematic by the presence of the British, although they began their evacuation of the area.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] According to his analysis, it was essential that they empty the zone of any Arab presence to completely protect themselves; the exodus would also encumber the roads that the Arab forces would have to penetrate.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 20 April, Allon launched a campaign that mixed propaganda, attacks, seizing control of strongholds that the British had abandoned, and destroying conquered Arab villages.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 1 May, a counter-offensive was launched by Arab militiamen against Jewish settlements but was ultimately unsuccessful.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 11 May, Safed fell, and the operation finished on 24 May after the villages of the valley of Hula were burnt down.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Syrian forces' planned offensive in the area failed and, by the end of June, Galilee panhandle from Tiberias to Metula, incorporating Safed, was emptied of all its Arab population.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 10 May, Golda Meir and Ezra Danin secretly went to Amman, to the palace of King Abdullah to discuss the situation with him.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The situation that Abdullah found himself in was difficult.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On one hand, his personal ambitions, the promises made by the Yishuv in November 1947 and the British approval of these promises pushed him to consider annexing the Arab part of Palestine without intervening against the future state of Israel.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On the other hand, the pressure exerted by his people in reaction to the massacre of Deir Yassin, combined with their feelings with regard to the Palestinian exodus and his agreements with other members of the Arab League pushed him to be more strongly involved in the war against Israel.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] He also found himself in a position of power, having the benefit of military support from not only the Arab League, but the British.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Historical analyses of the motivations and conclusions of this meeting differ.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] According to Dominique Lapierre and Larry Collins – as well as Israeli historiographers – the intention behind the Yishuv's negotiation was to obtain a peace treaty and avoid an attack by Arab forces.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] At that time, the balance of power was not favourable for them, but Meir did not manage to convince the King.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] According to Morris, Abdullah 'reconsidered the promises that he made in November to not be opposed to the partition plan,' but left Meir with the impression that he would make peace with the Jewish state once the civil war had finished.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Avi Shlaim spoke of a 'tacit' agreement to prevent the division of Palestine with the Palestinians, arguing the idea that there was a collusion between the Hashemite Kingdom and Yishuv.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The historian Yoav Gelber, however, rejected this idea and devoted an entire work to dismounting it.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Pierre Razoux indicated that 'the majority of experts consider it probable' that Ben-Gurion and King Abdullah had an understanding over dividing Palestine, and that only the pressure from the Arab states on Abdullah constrained him from following up on his promise.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] According to Razoux, this idea explains the attitude of the British, who, following this plan, would thereby fulfill the promises made by Arthur Balfour to the Yishuv and the Hashemite empire at the same time.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] He states that the presence of Arab Legion troops, before 15 May, near strategic positions held by the British is in this way easy to understand.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Ilan Pappé stressed that neither Abdullah's ministers, nor the Arab world itself, seemed to be privy to the discussions held between him and the Yishuv, even if his ambitions on Palestine were widely known.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] He also stated that Sir Alec Kirkbride and Glubb Pasha thought at the time that, at the very least, Azzam Pasha, the Secretary of the Arab League, must have known about Abdullah's double game.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] It is certain, on the other hand, that Golda Meir and King Abdullah did not come to an agreement on the status of Jerusalem.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 13 May, the Arab Legion took Kfar Etzion, strategically located halfway along the road between Hebron and Jerusalem.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 17 May, Abdullah ordered Glubb Pasha, commander of the Arab Legion, to launch an attack against the Holy City.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Kfar Etzion is a group of four settlements established on the strategic route between Hebron and Jerusalem, right in the middle of Arab inhabited territory.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] It had 400 inhabitants at the end of 1947.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] After the adoption of Resolution 181(II), it was the object of Arab attacks.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Ben-Gurion reinforced it on 7 December, protecting it with a Palmach division, but on 8 January, he authorized the evacuation of the women and children of the settlements.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] After 26 March, the last date on which a supply convoy successfully reached it, despite heavy losses of life, the defenders were completely isolated.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 12 May, Arab Legion units started to attack the settlements.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The motivations advanced include their desire to protect one of their last supply convoys before the embargo took effect, which had to travel down the road by Kfar Etzion.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Another theory is that the block of settlements obstructed the deployment of the Legion in the area around Hebron, whose attack was one of Abdullah's principal objectives.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] External defences fell quickly, and, on 13 May, the first kibbutz was captured.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Those who were taken prisoner were massacred; only four survived.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Of the 131 defenders, 127, including 21 women, were killed, or massacred after they surrendered.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The other three establishments surrendered, and the kibbutzim were first plundered, then razed to the ground.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In March 1949, 320 prisoners from the Etzion settlements were released from the "Jordan POW camp at Mafrak", including 85 women.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The events that took place at Kfar Etzion made apparent the limitations of the policy prohibiting evacuation.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Although it was effective during civil war, when facing militias, isolated Jewish settlements could not resist the firepower of a regular army, and an evacuation could have made it possible to avoid the captivity or death of those who defended the settlements.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Ben-Gurion left the final decision to Shaltiel.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The battle for Jerusalem was thus set in motion.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Operation Yevusi lasted two weeks, from 22 April 1948 to 3 May 1948.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Not all objectives were achieved before the British enforced a cease-fire.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] A Palmach force occupied the strategically located San Simon monastery in Katamon.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Arab irregulars attacked the monastery and a heavy battle evolved.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Both sides had a lot of wounded and killed fighters.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Palmach considered a retreat while the wounded fighters would blow themselves up, but then it was realized that the Arab force was exhausted and could not continue the fighting.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] As a result, the Arab residents left the suburb and the southern besieged Jewish suburbs were released.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Haganah intended to capture the Old City during the final days of the Mandate.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Its attacks on the seam between East and West Jerusalem from 13 to 18 May (known as Operation Kilshon) were planned as the initial phase of this conquest.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In Jerusalem, the British held several strategically located security zones named "Bevingrads", at its centre.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The city's radio station, telephone exchange and government hospital were located there, along with a number of barracks and the Notre Dame hostel, which dominated the city.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] One of the main objectives of Operation Kilshon was to take control of these zones of strategic importance while the British withdrew.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 13 May the Haganah extended its control of the Old City's Jewish Quarter and on 14th (having obtained the precise schedule of the evacuation with British complicity) took control of the Bevingrads, including the central post office and the Russian Church compound at 04:00.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] They surprised the Arab troops, who offered no resistance.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] A secondary objective of Operation Kilshon was to simultaneously create a continuous frontline between the various isolated Jewish localities.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] For this aim, Brigadier General David Shaltiel, Haganah's former envoy to Europe, was deployed along with a troop of 400 Haganah soldiers and 600 militia soldiers.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Emil Ghuri, the new leader of the Army of the Holy War, also envisaged taking these districts and mobilized 600 soldiers for the mission, but prepared no specific operation.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In the North of the city, Jewish forces seized Arab-populated Sheikh Jarrah, made a connection with Mount Scopus, and took the villages surrounding the American colony.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In the South, they ensured the connection of the German and Greek colonies with Talpiot and Ramat Rahel, after having taken the Allenby barracks.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] A Palmach unit even re-established contact with the Jewish district in the Old City via the Zion Gate.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The irregular Arabic forces were rendered impotent and yielded to panic, calling the situation hopeless and announcing the imminent fall of the city.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Within the framework of Plan Dalet, Yigael Yadin intended to make a breakthrough in the west of Galilee, wherein a number of isolated Jewish settlements were situated.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] This zone, which covers the land from Acre all the way to the Lebanese border, was allocated to the Arabs by the Partition plan, but was on the road through which Lebanese forces intended to enter into Palestine.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The command of this operation was entrusted to Moshe Carmel, head of the Carmeli brigade.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] It consisted of two phases: the first began on the evening of 13 May, when a column of Haganah's armoured vehicles and lorries advanced along the coast with no resistance.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The forces of the Arab Liberation Army fled without entering battle, and the first phase of the operation finished when Acre was taken on 18 May.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In the second phase, from 19 to 21 May, troops went as far as the Yehi'am kibbutz by the Lebanese border, connecting it and conquering and destroying a number of Arab villages on the way.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Haganah's move to offensive operations during the second phase of the war was accompanied by a huge exodus that involved 350,000 Arab refugees, adding to the 100,000 displaced during the First wave.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The term 'Palestinian exodus' is often used to refer to both these and two subsequent waves.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] These two waves gained a considerable amount of press interest and were widely relayed in the press of the time, more so than most other Palestine-related events.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The causes of and responsibility for this exodus are highly controversial topics among commentators on the conflict and even historians who specialize in this era.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Among the various possible causes, Efraim Karsh attributes the exodus mainly to Arab authorities' instructions to escape, whereas others argue that a policy of expulsion had been organized by the Yishuv authorities and implemented by Haganah.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Others yet reject these two assumptions and see the exodus as the cumulative effect of all the civil war's consequences.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] During the last meeting of the Arab League in February 1948, the Arab leaders expressed their convictions in the capacity of the Arab Liberation Army to help the Palestinians and to force the international community to give up on the UN-backed partition plan.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The following summit took place in Cairo on 10 April, with the situation having clearly developed with the death of Al-Husayni and the debacle at Mishmar Ha'emek.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Once again, Ismail Safwat called for the immediate deployment of the Arab state armies at the borders of Palestine, and for the need to go beyond the established policy of participating in little more than small-scale raids towards taking part in large-scale operations.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] For the first time, the Arab leaders discussed the possibility of intervening in Palestine.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Syria and Lebanon declared themselves ready to intervene immediately, but King Abdullah refused to let the Arab Legion forces intervene immediately in favour of the Palestinians, a move which irritated the Secretary-General of the League, who declared that Abdallah only cedes to the British diktat.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Nonetheless, Abdullah declared himself ready to send the Legion to assist the Palestinian cause after 15 May.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In response, Syria insisted that the Egyptian army also take part, and, in spite of the opposition of Egypt's prime minister, King Farouk responded favourably to the Syrian request, but due to his aim of curbing the Jordanians' hegemonic goals rather than his desire to help the Palestinians.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] It was decided that command over the operations would be reserved for King Abdullah, and that the Iraqis would deploy a brigade in Transjordan to prepare for intervention on 15 May.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 26 April, the 'intention to occupy Palestine' was officially announced at the Transjordanian parliament and the Jewish people were 'invited to place themselves beneath King Abdullah's jurisdiction.' The intention to spare their lives was also promised.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Yishuv perceived this declaration as being one of war and encourages the Western world to pressure the King, through diplomatic means, to prevent his intervention.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 30 April, Jordanians, Egyptians and Iraqis disputed the command of Abdullah.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Abdullah received the honorary title of Commander-in-Chief, while the Iraqi general, Aldine Nur Mahmud, was named Chief of Staff.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Despite this show of unity, it was agreed that each army would act independent of each other in the theatre of operations.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 4 May, the Iraqi task force arrived at Mafraq.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] It was composed of a regiment of armoured tanks, a regiment of mechanized infantry, and twenty-four artillery weapons, and included 1500 men.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Egyptians formed two brigades, deploying around 700 men into the Sinai.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Syrians could not put together a better force, whereas the Lebanese announced that they could not take part in military operations on 10 May.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] It was only two days before, on 8 May, that the British Foreign Office was certain of the Arab invasion.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The state of preparation of the army was such that they did not even have maps of Palestine.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] At the time, the final plans of invasion had not even been established yet.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] British leaders tried in vain to make the Arab leaders reconsider their decision, and Ismail Safwat resigned in indifference, but the Arab states seemed resolute.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 15 May 1948, the Arab League announced officially that it would intervene in Palestine to guarantee the security and right to self-determination of the inhabitants of Palestine in an independent state.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] According to Benny Morris, the result of these five and a half months of fighting was a "decisive Jewish victory".
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On one side, the "Palestinian Arab military power was crushed" and most of the population in the combat zones was fleeing or had been driven out.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] According to Yoav Gelber, during the six weeks between the Haganah offensive on 1 April and the invasion of the Arab armies, the Arabs were defeated in almost every front.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Jewish forces captured four cities (Tiberias, Jaffa, Safed, and Haifa) and 190 villages; most of their residents fled.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The refugees flooded Samaria, central Galilee, Mount Hebron region, Gaza region, as well as Transjordan, Lebanon, and southern Syria.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] With the defeat of the Palestinian forces and the ALA, the Arab League saw no other option than to invade at the end of the British Mandate.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The process of deciding to invade and preparing for the attack began two or three weeks before the end of the Mandate, when the level of the defeat was revealed and it was clear the ALA could not prevent it.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Although the Haganah was somewhat poorly armed, its offensive of the last weeks went well, because Arab villages did not come to the help of their neighboring Arab villages or towns.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Moreover, only a few young Arab men from untouched areas (e.g.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Nablus, Hebron) participated in the fighting in Jerusalem, Haifa, etc.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Anwar Nusseibeh, a supporter of the Mufti, said the Mufti refused to issue arms to anyone except his political supporters and only recruited his supporters for the forces of the Holy War Army.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] This partially accounts for the absence of an organized Arab force and for the insufficient amount of arms, which plagued the Arab defenders of Jerusalem.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 14 May 1948, David Ben-Gurion, on behalf of the Jewish leadership, declared the establishment of the State of Israel.
[src:british-empire/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The 1948 Palestine war entered its second phase with the intervention of the Arab state armies and the beginning of the 1948 Arab–Israeli War.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The **British Empire** comprised the dominions, colonies, protectorates, mandates, and other territories ruled or administered by the United Kingdom and its predecessor states.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] It began with the overseas possessions and trading posts established by England in the late 16th and early 17th centuries, and colonisation attempts by Scotland during the 17th century.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] At its height in the 19th and early 20th centuries, it was the largest empire in history and, for a century, was the foremost global power.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] By 1913, the British Empire held sway over 412 million people, 23 per cent of the world population at the time, and by 1920, it covered 35.5 million km2 (13.7 million sq mi), 24 per cent of the Earth's total land area.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] As a result, its constitutional, legal, linguistic, and cultural legacy is widespread.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] It was described as "the empire on which the sun never sets", as the sun was always shining on at least one of its territories.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] During the Age of Discovery in the 15th and 16th centuries, Portugal and Spain pioneered European exploration of the world, and in the process established large overseas empires.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Motivated by the great wealth these empires generated, England, France, and the Netherlands began to establish colonies and trade networks in the Americas and Asia.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] A series of wars in the 17th and 18th centuries with the Netherlands and France left Britain the dominant colonial power in North America.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Britain became a major power in the Indian subcontinent after the East India Company's conquest of Mughal Bengal at the Battle of Plassey in 1757.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The American Revolution resulted in Britain losing some of its oldest and most populous colonies in North America by 1783.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] While retaining control of British North America (now Canada) and territories in and near the Caribbean in the British West Indies, British colonial expansion turned towards Asia, Africa, and the Pacific.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] After the defeat of France in the Napoleonic Wars (1803–1815), Britain emerged as the principal naval and imperial power of the 19th century and expanded its imperial holdings.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] It pursued trade concessions in China and Japan, and territory in Southeast Asia.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The Great Game and Scramble for Africa also ensued.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The period of relative peace (1815–1914) during which the British Empire became the global hegemon was later described as *Pax Britannica* (Latin for "British Peace").
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Alongside the formal control that Britain exerted over its colonies, its dominance of much of world trade, and of its oceans, meant that it effectively controlled the economies of, and readily enforced its interests in, many regions, such as Asia and Latin America.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] It also came to dominate the Middle East, shaping its modern borders alongside France.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Increasing degrees of autonomy were recognised for its white settler colonies, some of which were formally reclassified as Dominions by the 1920s.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] By the start of the 20th century, Germany and the United States had begun to challenge Britain's economic lead.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Military, economic and colonial tensions between Britain and Germany were major causes of the First World War, during which Britain relied heavily on its empire.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The conflict placed enormous strain on its military, financial, and manpower resources.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Although the empire achieved its largest territorial extent immediately after the First World War, Britain was no longer the world's preeminent industrial or military power.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In the Second World War, Britain's colonies in East Asia and Southeast Asia were occupied by the Empire of Japan.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Despite the final victory of Britain and its allies, the damage to British prestige and the British economy helped accelerate the decline of the empire.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] India, Britain's most valuable and populous possession, achieved independence in 1947 as part of a larger decolonisation movement, in which Britain granted independence to most territories of the empire.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The Suez Crisis of 1956 confirmed Britain's decline as a global power, and the handover of Hong Kong to China on 1 July 1997 symbolised for many the end of the British Empire, though fourteen overseas territories that are remnants of the empire remain under British sovereignty.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] After independence, many former British colonies, along with most of the dominions, joined the Commonwealth of Nations, a free association of independent states.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Fifteen of these, including the United Kingdom, retain the same person as monarch, currently King Charles III.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The foundations of the overseas British Empire were laid when England and Scotland were separate kingdoms, and, at the time ruled by different monarchs.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In 1496, King Henry VII of England, following the successes of Spain and Portugal in overseas exploration, commissioned John Cabot to lead an expedition to discover a Northwest Passage to Asia via the North Atlantic.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Cabot sailed in 1497, five years after the first voyage of Christopher Columbus, and made landfall on the coast of Newfoundland.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] He believed he had reached Asia, and there was no attempt to found a colony.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Cabot led another voyage to the Americas the following year but did not return; it is unknown what happened to his ships.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] There is "inferential evidence [that] suggests that Bristol mariners may already have known of that North American shore and had been harvesting its rich seas for a decade or more", but England made no formal claims.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] No further attempts to establish English colonies in the Americas were made until well into the reign of Queen Elizabeth I, during the last decades of the 16th century.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In the meantime, Henry VIII's 1533 Statute in Restraint of Appeals had declared "that this realm of England is an Empire".
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The Protestant Reformation turned England and Catholic Spain into implacable enemies.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In 1562, Elizabeth I encouraged the privateers John Hawkins and Francis Drake to engage in slave-raiding attacks against Spanish and Portuguese ships off the coast of West Africa with the aim of establishing an Atlantic slave trade.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] This effort was rebuffed and later, as the Anglo-Spanish Wars intensified, Elizabeth I gave her blessing to further privateering raids against Spanish ports in the Americas and shipping that was returning across the Atlantic, laden with treasure from the New World.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] At the same time, influential writers such as Richard Hakluyt and John Dee (who was the first to use the term "British Empire") were beginning to press for the establishment of England's own empire.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] By this time, Spain had become the dominant power in the Americas and was exploring the Pacific Ocean, Portugal had established trading posts and forts from the coasts of Africa and Brazil to China, and France had begun to settle the Saint Lawrence River area, later to become New France.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Although England tended to trail behind Portugal, Spain, and France in establishing overseas colonies, it carried out its first modern colonisation, in sixteenth-century Ireland, with settlements, known as "plantations", of English and Welsh Protestants.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] England had already colonised part of the country following the Norman invasion of Ireland in 1169, but English authority had waned over the centuries.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] During the reign of Elizabeth I, a pattern of conquest and attempts at colonization was "contemporaneous with and parallel to the first effective of Englishmen in North America".
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Several men who helped establish the Munster plantations in Ireland later played a part in the early colonisation of North America, particularly a group known as the West Country Men.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In 1578, Elizabeth I granted a patent to Humphrey Gilbert for discovery and overseas exploration.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] That year, Gilbert sailed for the Caribbean with the intention of engaging in piracy and establishing a colony in North America, but the expedition was aborted before it had crossed the Atlantic.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In 1583, he embarked on a second attempt.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] On this occasion, he formally claimed the harbour of the island of Newfoundland, although no settlers were left behind.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Gilbert did not survive the return journey to England and was succeeded by his half-brother, Walter Raleigh, who was granted his own patent by Elizabeth in 1584.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Later that year, Raleigh founded the Roanoke Colony on the coast of present-day North Carolina, but lack of supplies caused the colony to fail.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] From 1585 to 1603, England fully conquered Ireland and challenged the naval dominance of Spain in the Anglo-Spanish War, with their war ending in a draw.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In 1603, James VI of Scotland ascended (as James I) to the English throne and in 1604 negotiated the Treaty of London, ending hostilities with Spain.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Now at peace with its main rival, English attention shifted from preying on other nations' colonial infrastructures to the business of establishing its own overseas colonies.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The British Empire began to take shape during the early 17th century, with the English settlement of North America and the smaller islands of the Caribbean, and the establishment of joint-stock companies, most notably the East India Company, to administer colonies and overseas trade.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] This period, until the loss of the Thirteen Colonies after the American War of Independence towards the end of the 18th century, has been referred to by some historians as the "First British Empire".
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] England's early efforts at colonisation in the Americas met with mixed success.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] An attempt to establish a colony in Guiana in 1604 lasted only two years and failed in its main objective to find gold deposits.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Colonies on the Caribbean islands of St Lucia (1605) and Grenada (1609) rapidly folded.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The first permanent English settlement in the Americas was founded in 1607 in Jamestown by Captain John Smith, and managed by the Virginia Company; the Crown took direct control of the venture in 1624, thereby founding the Colony of Virginia.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Bermuda was settled and claimed by England as a result of the 1609 shipwreck of the Virginia Company's flagship, while attempts to settle Newfoundland were largely unsuccessful.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In 1620, Plymouth was founded as a haven by Puritan religious separatists, later known as the Pilgrims.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Fleeing religious persecution became a major motive for many English would-be colonists to risk the arduous trans-Atlantic voyage: Maryland was established by English Roman Catholics (1634), Rhode Island (1636) as a colony tolerant of all religions and Connecticut (1639) for Congregationalists.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] England's North American holdings were further expanded by the annexation of the Dutch colony of New Netherland in 1664, following the capture of New Amsterdam, which was renamed New York.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Although less financially successful than colonies in the Caribbean, these territories had large areas of good agricultural land and attracted far greater numbers of English emigrants, who preferred their temperate climates.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The British West Indies initially provided England's most important and lucrative colonies.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Settlements were successfully established in St.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Kitts (1624), Barbados (1627) and Nevis (1628), but struggled until the "Sugar Revolution" transformed the Caribbean economy in the mid-17th century.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Large sugarcane plantations were first established in the 1640s on Barbados, with assistance from Dutch merchants and Sephardic Jews fleeing Portuguese Brazil.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] At first, sugar was grown primarily using white indentured labour, but rising costs soon led English traders to embrace the use of imported African slaves.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The enormous wealth generated by slave-produced sugar made Barbados the most successful colony in the Americas, and one of the most densely populated places in the world.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] To ensure that the increasingly healthy profits of colonial trade remained in English hands, Parliament decreed in 1651 that only English ships would be able to ply their trade in English colonies.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] This led to hostilities with the United Dutch Provinces—a series of Anglo-Dutch Wars—which would eventually strengthen England's position in the Americas at the expense of the Dutch.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In 1655, England annexed the island of Jamaica from the Spanish, and in 1666 succeeded in colonising the Bahamas.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In 1670, Charles II incorporated by royal charter the Hudson's Bay Company (HBC), granting it a monopoly on the fur trade in the area known as Rupert's Land, which would later form a large proportion of the Dominion of Canada.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Forts and trading posts established by the HBC were frequently the subject of attacks by the French, who had established their own fur trading colony in adjacent New France.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Two years later, the Royal African Company was granted a monopoly on the supply of slaves to the British colonies in the Caribbean.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The company would transport more slaves across the Atlantic than any other, and significantly grew England's share of the trade, from 33 per cent in 1673 to 74 per cent in 1683.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The removal of this monopoly between 1688 and 1712 allowed independent British slave traders to thrive, leading to a rapid escalation in the number of slaves transported.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In the Atlantic slave trade, British ships carried a third of all slaves shipped across the Atlantic—approximately 3.5 million Africans—until the abolition of the trade by Parliament in 1807 (see § Abolition of slavery).
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] To facilitate the shipment of slaves, forts were established on the coast of West Africa, such as James Island, Accra and Bunce Island.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In the British Caribbean, the percentage of the population of African descent rose from 25 per cent in 1650 to around 80 per cent in 1780, and in the Thirteen Colonies from 10 per cent to 40 per cent over the same period (the majority in the southern colonies).
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The transatlantic slave trade played a pervasive role in British economic life, and became a major economic mainstay for western port cities.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Ships registered in Bristol, Liverpool and London were responsible for the bulk of British slave trading.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] For the transported, harsh and unhygienic conditions on the slaving ships and poor diets meant that the average mortality rate during the Middle Passage was one in seven.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] After the abolition of slavery in the British Empire, plantation owners in the Caribbean used indentured labour from India as a replacement workforce.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] From the mid-19th century, more than 500,000 Indians were brought in to British Guiana, Trinidad and other colonies.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The primary aim of these companies was to tap into the lucrative spice trade, an effort focused mainly on two regions: the East Indies archipelago, and an important hub in the trade network, India.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] There, they competed for trade supremacy with Portugal and with each other.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Although England eclipsed the Netherlands as a colonial power, in the short term the Netherlands' more advanced financial system and the three Anglo-Dutch Wars of the 17th century left it with a stronger position in Asia.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Hostilities ceased after the Glorious Revolution of 1688 when the Dutch William of Orange ascended the English throne, bringing peace between the Dutch Republic and England.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] A deal between the two nations left the spice trade of the East Indies archipelago to the Netherlands and the textiles industry of India to England, but textiles soon overtook spices in terms of profitability.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In 1701, England, Portugal and the Netherlands sided with the Holy Roman Empire against Spain and France in the War of the Spanish Succession, which lasted for thirteen years.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Colonisation attempts by the Kingdom of Scotland predates the establishment of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and the British Empire.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] During the 17th century, the Kingdom of Scotland made attempts to establish trading schemes in Ireland and Canada.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Nova Scotia, today a province of Canada, was a short lived scheme in the Mi'kmaq people territory.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Additionally, there was a high number of Scots in Ireland, particularly in the region of Ulster, who settled there as planters.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The first documented Scottish settlement in the Americas was of Nova Scotia in 1629.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] On 29 September 1621, the charter for the foundation of a colony was granted by James VI of Scotland to Sir William Alexander.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Between 1622 and 1628, Sir William launched four attempts to send colonists to Nova Scotia; all failed for various reasons.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] A successful settlement of Nova Scotia was finally achieved in 1629.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The colony's charter, in law, made Nova Scotia (defined as all land between Newfoundland and New England; i.e., The Maritimes) a part of mainland Scotland; this was later used to get around the English navigation acts.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] As a country, Scotland engaged in two ventures in an attempt to establish colonies within English colonies during the 1680s in Carolina and East New Jersey.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The Act restricted Scottish trade with English colonies.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Scottish settlement attempts in Carolina began in 1682, and was eventually defeated by the dissolution of the Scottish settlement of Stewartstoun, which was established in 1684, by the Spanish in 1686.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In 1695, the Parliament of Scotland granted a charter to the Company of Scotland, which established a settlement in 1698 on the Isthmus of Panama.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Besieged by neighbouring Spanish colonists of New Granada, and affected by malaria, the colony was abandoned two years later.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The Darien scheme was a financial disaster for Scotland: a quarter of Scottish capital was lost in the enterprise.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The episode had major political consequences, helping to persuade the government of the Kingdom of Scotland of the merits of turning the personal union with England into a political and economic one under the Kingdom of Great Britain established by the Acts of Union 1707.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The 18th century saw the newly united Great Britain rise to be the world's dominant colonial power, with France becoming its main rival on the imperial stage.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Great Britain, Portugal, the Netherlands, and the Holy Roman Empire continued the War of the Spanish Succession, which lasted until 1714 and was concluded by the Treaty of Utrecht.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Philip V of Spain renounced his and his descendants' claim to the French throne, and Spain lost its empire in Europe.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The British Empire was territorially enlarged: from France, Britain gained Newfoundland and Acadia, and from Spain, Gibraltar and Menorca.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Gibraltar became a critical naval base and allowed Britain to control the Atlantic entry and exit point to the Mediterranean.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Spain ceded the rights to the lucrative *asiento* (permission to sell African slaves in Spanish America) to Britain.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] With the outbreak of the Anglo-Spanish War of Jenkins' Ear in 1739, Spanish privateers attacked British merchant shipping along the Triangle Trade routes.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In 1746, the Spanish and British began peace talks, with the King of Spain agreeing to stop all attacks on British shipping; however, in the 1750 Treaty of Madrid, Britain lost its slave-trading rights in Latin America.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In the East Indies, British and Dutch merchants continued to compete in spices and textiles.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] With textiles becoming the larger trade, by 1720, in terms of sales, the British company had overtaken the Dutch.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] During the middle decades of the 18th century, there were several outbreaks of military conflict on the Indian subcontinent, as the English East India Company and its French counterpart, struggled alongside local rulers to fill the vacuum that had been left by the decline of the Mughal Empire.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The Battle of Plassey in 1757, in which the British defeated the Nawab of Bengal and his French allies, left the British East India Company in control of Bengal and as a major military and political power in India.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] France was left control of its enclaves but with military restrictions and an obligation to support British client states, ending French hopes of controlling India.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The British and French struggles in India became but one theatre of the global Seven Years' War (1756–1763) involving France, Britain, and the other major European powers.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The signing of the Treaty of Paris of 1763 had important consequences for the future of the British Empire.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In North America, France's future as a colonial power effectively ended with the recognition of British claims to Rupert's Land, and the ceding of New France to Britain (leaving a sizeable French-speaking population under British control) and Louisiana to Spain.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Along with its victory over France in India, the Seven Years' War therefore left Britain as the world's most powerful maritime power.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] During the 1760s and early 1770s, relations between the Thirteen Colonies and Britain became increasingly strained, primarily because of resentment of the British Parliament's attempts to govern and tax American colonists without their consent.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] This was summarised at the time by the colonists' slogan "No taxation without representation", a perceived violation of the guaranteed Rights of Englishmen.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The American Revolution began with a rejection of Parliamentary authority and moves towards self-government.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In response, Britain sent troops to reimpose direct rule, leading to the outbreak of war in 1775.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The following year, in 1776, the Second Continental Congress issued the Declaration of Independence proclaiming the colonies' sovereignty from the British Empire as the new United States of America.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The entry of French and Spanish forces into the war tipped the military balance in the Americans' favour and after a decisive defeat at Yorktown in 1781, Britain began negotiating peace terms.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] American independence was acknowledged at the Peace of Paris in 1783.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Adam Smith's *Wealth of Nations*, published in 1776, had argued that colonies were redundant, and that free trade should replace the old mercantilist policies that had characterised the first period of colonial expansion, dating back to the protectionism of Spain and Portugal.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The growth of trade between the newly independent United States and Britain after 1783 seemed to confirm Smith's view that political control was not necessary for economic success.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The war to the south influenced British policy in Canada, where between 40,000 and 100,000 defeated Loyalists had migrated from the new United States following independence.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The 14,000 Loyalists who went to the Saint John and Saint Croix river valleys, then part of Nova Scotia, felt too far removed from the provincial government in Halifax, so London split off New Brunswick as a separate colony in 1784.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Tensions between Britain and the United States escalated again during the Napoleonic Wars, as Britain tried to cut off American trade with France and boarded American ships to impress men into the Royal Navy.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The United States Congress declared war, the War of 1812, and invaded Canadian territory.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In response, Britain invaded the US, but the pre-war boundaries were reaffirmed by the 1814 Treaty of Ghent, ensuring Canada's future would be separate from that of the United States.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Since 1718, transportation and exile to the American colonies had been a penalty for various offences in Britain, with about one thousand convicts transported per year.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Forced to find an alternative location after the loss of the Thirteen Colonies in 1783, the British government looked for an alternative, eventually turning to Australia.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] On his first of three voyages commissioned by the government, James Cook reached New Zealand in October 1769.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] He was the first European to circumnavigate and map the country.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] From the late 18th century, the country was regularly visited by explorers and other sailors, missionaries, traders and adventurers but no attempt was made to settle the country or establish possession.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The coast of Australia had been discovered for Europeans by the Dutch in 1606, but there was no attempt to colonise it.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In 1770, after leaving New Zealand, Cook charted the eastern coast, claimed the continent for Britain, and named it New South Wales.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In 1778, Joseph Banks, Cook's botanist on the voyage, presented evidence to the government on the suitability of Botany Bay for the establishment of a penal settlement, and in 1787 the first shipment of convicts set sail, arriving in 1788.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Unusually, Australia was claimed through proclamation.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Indigenous Australians were considered too uncivilised to require treaties, and colonisation brought disease and violence that together with the deliberate dispossession of land and culture were devastating to these peoples.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Britain continued to transport convicts to New South Wales until 1840, to Tasmania until 1853 and to Western Australia until 1868.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The Australian colonies became profitable exporters of wool and gold, mainly because of the Victorian gold rush, making its capital Melbourne for a time the richest city in the world.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The British also expanded their mercantile interests in the North Pacific.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Spain and Britain had become rivals in the area, culminating in the Nootka Crisis in 1789.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Both sides mobilised for war, but when France refused to support Spain, it was forced to back down, leading to the Nootka Convention.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The outcome was a humiliation for Spain, which practically renounced all sovereignty on the North Pacific coast.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] This opened the way to British expansion in the area, and a number of expeditions took place; firstly a naval expedition led by George Vancouver which explored the inlets around the Pacific North West, particularly around Vancouver Island.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] On land, expeditions sought to discover a river route to the Pacific for the extension of the North American fur trade.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Alexander Mackenzie of the North West Company led the first, starting out in 1792, and a year later he became the first European to reach the Pacific overland north of the Rio Grande, reaching the ocean near present-day Bella Coola.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] This preceded the Lewis and Clark Expedition by twelve years.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Shortly thereafter, Mackenzie's companion, John Finlay, founded the first permanent European settlement in British Columbia, Fort St.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The North West Company sought further exploration and backed expeditions by David Thompson, starting in 1797, and later by Simon Fraser.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] These pushed into the wilderness territories of the Rocky Mountains and Interior Plateau to the Strait of Georgia on the Pacific Coast, expanding British North America westward.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] in 1765 (left) and 1858 (right) showing British expansion in the region.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The East India Company fought a series of Anglo-Mysore Wars in Southern India with the Sultanate of Mysore under Hyder Ali and then Tipu Sultan.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Defeats in the First Anglo-Mysore War and stalemate in the Second were followed by victories in the Third and the Fourth.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Following Tipu Sultan's death in the fourth war in the Siege of Seringapatam (1799), the kingdom became a protectorate of the company.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The East India Company fought three Anglo-Maratha Wars with the Maratha Confederacy.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The First Anglo-Maratha War ended in 1782 with a restoration of the pre-war *status quo*.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The Second and Third Anglo-Maratha wars resulted in British victories.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] After the surrender of Peshwa Bajirao II in 1818, the East India Company acquired control of a large majority of the Indian subcontinent.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Britain was challenged again by France under Napoleon, in a struggle that, unlike previous wars, represented a contest of ideologies between the two nations.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] It was not only Britain's position on the world stage that was at risk: Napoleon threatened to invade Britain itself, just as his armies had overrun many countries of continental Europe.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The Napoleonic Wars were therefore ones in which Britain invested large amounts of capital and resources to win.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] French ports were blockaded by the Royal Navy, which won a decisive victory over a French Imperial Navy-Spanish Navy fleet at the Battle of Trafalgar in 1805.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Overseas colonies were attacked and occupied, including those of the Netherlands, which was annexed by Napoleon in 1810.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] France was finally defeated by a coalition of European armies in 1815.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Britain was again the beneficiary of peace treaties: France ceded the Ionian Islands, Malta (which it had occupied in 1798), Mauritius, St Lucia, the Seychelles, and Tobago; Spain ceded Trinidad; the Netherlands ceded Guiana, Ceylon and the Cape Colony, while the Danish ceded Heligoland.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Britain returned Guadeloupe, Martinique, French Guiana, and Réunion to France; Menorca to Spain; Danish West Indies to Denmark and Java and Suriname to the Netherlands.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] With the advent of the Industrial Revolution, goods produced by slavery became less important to the British economy.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Added to this was the cost of suppressing regular slave rebellions.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] With support from the British abolitionist movement, Parliament enacted the Slave Trade Act in 1807, which abolished the slave trade in the empire.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In 1808, Sierra Leone Colony was designated an official British colony for freed slaves.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Parliamentary reform in 1832 saw the influence of the West India Committee decline.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The Slavery Abolition Act, passed the following year, abolished slavery in the British Empire on 1 August 1834, finally bringing the empire into line with the law in the UK (with the exception of the territories administered by the East India Company and Ceylon, where slavery was ended in 1844).
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Under the Act, slaves were granted full emancipation after a period of four to six years of "apprenticeship".
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Facing further opposition from abolitionists, the apprenticeship system was abolished in 1838.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The British government compensated slave-owners.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] During Britain's "imperial century" between 1815 and 1914, around 10 million sq mi (26 million km2) of territory and roughly 400 million people were added to the British Empire.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Victory over Napoleon left Britain without any serious international rival, other than Russia in Central Asia.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Unchallenged at sea, Britain became the global policeman, a state of affairs later known as the *Pax Britannica*, and a foreign policy of "splendid isolation".
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Alongside the formal control it exerted over its own colonies, Britain's dominant position in world trade meant that it effectively controlled the economies of many countries, such as China, Argentina and Siam, which were seen as its "Informal Empire".
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] British imperial strength was underpinned by the steamship and the telegraph, new technologies invented in the second half of the 19th century, allowing it to control and defend the empire.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] By 1902, the British Empire was linked together by a network of telegraph cables, the All Red Line.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The East India Company drove the expansion of the British Empire in Asia.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] From its base in India, the company had been engaged in an increasingly profitable opium export trade to Qing China since the 1730s.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] This trade, illegal since it was outlawed by China in 1729, helped reverse the trade imbalances resulting from the British imports of tea, which saw large outflows of silver from Britain to China.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In 1839, the confiscation by the Chinese authorities at Canton of 20,000 chests of opium led Britain to attack China in the First Opium War, and resulted in the seizure by Britain of Hong Kong Island, at that time a minor settlement, and other treaty ports including Shanghai.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] During the late 18th and early 19th centuries, the British Crown began to assume an increasingly large role in the affairs of the company.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] A series of acts of Parliament were passed, including the Regulating Act 1773, East India Company Act 1784 and the Charter Act 1813 which regulated the company's affairs and established the sovereignty of the Crown over the territories that it had acquired.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The company's eventual end was precipitated by the Indian Rebellion in 1857, a conflict that had begun with the mutiny of sepoys, Indian troops under British officers and discipline.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The rebellion took six months to suppress, with heavy loss of life on both sides.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The following year the British government dissolved the company and assumed direct control over India through the Government of India Act 1858, establishing the British Raj, where an appointed governor-general administered India and Queen Victoria was crowned the Empress of India.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] India became the empire's most valuable possession, "the Jewel in the Crown", and was the most important source of Britain's strength.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] A series of serious crop failures in the late 19th century led to widespread famines on the subcontinent in which it is estimated that over 15 million people died.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The East India Company had failed to implement any coordinated policy to deal with the famines during its period of rule.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Later, under direct British rule, commissions were set up after each famine to investigate the causes and implement new policies, which took until the early 1900s to have an effect.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] On each of his three voyages to the Pacific between 1769 and 1777, James Cook visited New Zealand.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] He was followed by an assortment of Europeans and Americans which including whalers, sealers, escaped convicts from New South Wales, missionaries and adventurers.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Initially, contact with the indigenous Māori people was limited to the trading of goods, although interaction increased during the early decades of the 19th century with many trading and missionary stations being set up, especially in the north.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The first of several Church of England missionaries arrived in 1814 and as well as their missionary role, they soon become the only form of European authority in a land that was not subject to British jurisdiction: the closest authority being the New South Wales governor in Sydney.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The sale of weapons to Māori resulted from 1818 on in the intertribal warfare of the Musket Wars, with devastating consequences for the Māori population.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The UK government finally decided to act, dispatching Captain William Hobson with instructions to take formal possession after obtaining native consent.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] There was no central Māori authority able to represent all New Zealand so, on 6 February 1840, Hobson and many Māori chiefs signed the Treaty of Waitangi in the Bay of Islands; most other chiefs signing in stages over the following months.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] William Hobson declared British sovereignty over all New Zealand on 21 May 1840, over the North Island by cession and over the South Island by discovery (the island was sparsely populated and deemed terra nullius).
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] Hobson became Lieutenant-Governor, subject to Governor Sir George Gipps in Sydney, with British possession of New Zealand initially administered from Australia as a dependency of the New South Wales colony.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] From 16 June 1840 New South Wales laws applied in New Zealand.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] This transitional arrangement ended with the Charter for Erecting the Colony of New Zealand on 16 November 1840.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The Charter stated that New Zealand would be established as a separate Crown colony on 3 May 1841 with Hobson as its governor.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] During the 19th century, Britain and the Russian Empire vied to fill the power vacuums that had been left by the declining Ottoman Empire, Qajar dynasty and Qing dynasty.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] This rivalry in Central Asia came to be known as the "Great Game".
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] As far as Britain was concerned, defeats inflicted by Russia on Persia and Turkey demonstrated its imperial ambitions and capabilities and stoked fears in Britain of an overland invasion of India.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] In 1839, Britain moved to pre-empt this by invading Afghanistan, but the First Anglo-Afghan War was a disaster for Britain.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] When Russia invaded the Ottoman Balkans in 1853, fears of Russian dominance in the Mediterranean and the Middle East led Britain and France to enter the war in support of the Ottoman Empire and invade the Crimean Peninsula to destroy Russian naval capabilities.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The ensuing Crimean War (1854–1856), which involved new techniques of modern warfare, was the only global war fought between Britain and another imperial power during the *Pax Britannica* and was a resounding defeat for Russia.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The situation remained unresolved in Central Asia for two more decades, with Britain annexing Baluchistan in 1876 and Russia annexing Kirghizia, Kazakhstan, and Turkmenistan.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] For a while, it appeared that another war would be inevitable, but the two countries reached an agreement on their respective spheres of influence in the region in 1878 and on all outstanding matters in 1907 with the signing of the Anglo-Russian Entente.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The destruction of the Imperial Russian Navy by the Imperial Japanese Navy at the Battle of Tsushima during the Russo-Japanese War of 1904–1905 limited its threat to the British.
[src:british-empire/british-empire-p01] The Dutch East India Company had founded the Dutch Cape Colony on the southern tip of Africa in 1652 as a way station for its ships travelling to and from its colonies in the East Indies.
